// Unit 13: Die Bewerbung
// Level: B1

const UNIT_13 =
{n:13,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Die Bewerbung",sub:"Job application, formal German, mock interview, Konjunktiv II",icon:"📝",level:"B1.1",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[

// ==================== LESSON 1: Der rote Stift ====================
{id:"deu_r13l1",title:"Der rote Stift",icon:"🖊️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der rote Stift",desc:"Verumius sits in Dr. Yilmaz's office. His CV is covered in red corrections. Time to discover the world of German job applications.",goals:["Learn key vocabulary for applications and job interviews","Understand what makes a German application unique","Follow Verumius through his first application"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-vhs-office",trg:"Dr. Yilmaz' Büro in der Volkshochschule. Nachmittagslicht fällt durch die Jalousien. Bücher überall. Eine kleine Goethe-Büste beobachtet vom Regal. Verumius sitzt Dr. Yilmaz gegenüber, sein Lebenslauf-Entwurf liegt zwischen ihnen. Rote Markierungen bedecken fast jede Zeile.",src:"Dr. Yilmaz's office at the adult education center. Afternoon light falls through the blinds. Books everywhere. A small Goethe bust watches from the shelf. Verumius sits across from Dr. Yilmaz, his CV draft lies between them. Red marks cover nearly every line."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"patient",trg:"Verumius, deine Bewerbung ist... kreativ. Aber in Deutschland ist eine Bewerbung ein offizielles Dokument. Sie muss perfekt sein.",src:"Verumius, your application is... creative. But in Germany, an application is an official document. It must be perfect."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",trg:"Aber ich habe alles geschrieben. Meinen Namen, meine Arbeit...",src:"But I wrote everything. My name, my work..."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"firm",trg:"Ein deutscher Lebenslauf braucht Struktur. Foto, Personaldaten, Ausbildung, Berufserfahrung. Alles korrekt, alles vollständig.",src:"A German CV needs structure. Photo, personal data, education, work experience. Everything correct, everything complete."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bewerbung",src:"the application",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'bewerben' (to apply).\nBe- + werben (to advertise/recruit).",example:"A: Ich schreibe eine Bewerbung.\nB: Für welche Firma?\nA: Für Siemens in Berlin.\nB: Viel Erfolg!",exampleSrc:"A: I am writing an application.\nB: For which company?\nA: For Siemens in Berlin.\nB: Good luck!",funFact:"A German Bewerbung always includes a cover letter (Anschreiben), CV (Lebenslauf), and certificates (Zeugnisse). It is a three-part package. You are literally 'advertising yourself.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Lebenslauf",src:"the CV, the resume",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Literally 'life-run' (Leben + Lauf).\nThe story of your life on paper.",example:"A: Haben Sie Ihren Lebenslauf mitgebracht?\nB: Ja, hier ist er. Zwei Seiten.\nA: Sehr gut. Mit Foto?\nB: Natürlich. Wie in Deutschland üblich.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you bring your CV?\nB: Yes, here it is. Two pages.\nA: Very good. With a photo?\nB: Of course. As is customary in Germany.",funFact:"Germans traditionally include a photo, date of birth, and marital status on their CV. This surprises many non-Germans. The Lebenslauf is literally the 'run of your life' on paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Erfolg",src:"the success",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'erfolgen' (to result).\n'Viel Erfolg!' = Good luck!",example:"A: Morgen habe ich mein Vorstellungsgespräch.\nB: Viel Erfolg! Du schaffst das.\nA: Danke. Ich bin so nervös.\nB: Erfolg kommt mit Vorbereitung.",exampleSrc:"A: Tomorrow I have my job interview.\nB: Good luck! You can do it.\nA: Thanks. I am so nervous.\nB: Success comes with preparation.",funFact:"'Viel Erfolg!' (Much success!) is how Germans wish you good luck before an interview. Success is literally 'what follows' from your effort."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich schreibe einen {1} für die Firma in Berlin.",a:["Lebenslauf"],opts:["Lebenslauf","Eindruck","Erfolg","Bewerbung"],hint:"The German word for CV literally means 'life-run.' It is a masculine noun.",sSrc:"I am writing a CV for the company in Berlin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Karriere",src:"the career",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Borrowed from French 'carriere'.\nSame root as English 'career.'",example:"A: Was ist Ihr Karriereziel?\nB: Ich möchte Teamleiterin werden.\nA: Gute Karriereplanung ist wichtig.\nB: Ja, ich habe einen klaren Plan.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your career goal?\nB: I want to become a team leader.\nA: Good career planning is important.\nB: Yes, I have a clear plan.",funFact:"Germans distinguish between Karriere (ambitious upward path) and Beruf (your profession). Not every Beruf is a Karriere. The French origin 'carriere' originally meant 'racecourse.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Eindruck",src:"the impression",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Ein (in) + Druck (pressure/print).\n'Der erste Eindruck zählt.'",example:"A: Wie war dein Eindruck vom Gespräch?\nB: Gut. Der Chef war freundlich.\nA: Der erste Eindruck zählt.\nB: Ja, ich habe mich gut vorbereitet.",exampleSrc:"A: What was your impression of the meeting?\nB: Good. The boss was friendly.\nA: The first impression counts.\nB: Yes, I prepared well.",funFact:"'Der erste Eindruck zählt' (The first impression counts) is a universal German saying. An impression is literally something 'pressed into' you."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vorbereitung",src:"the preparation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Vor (before) + Bereitung (preparation).\nPreparing before the event.",example:"A: Hast du dich vorbereitet?\nB: Ja, die Vorbereitung hat drei Tage gedauert.\nA: Gut. Ohne Vorbereitung kein Erfolg.\nB: Das stimmt. Ich bin jetzt bereit.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you prepare?\nB: Yes, the preparation took three days.\nA: Good. Without preparation, no success.\nB: That's right. I am ready now.",funFact:"Germans are famous for Vorbereitung. A job interview without preparation is unthinkable. The compound tells you: do it BEFORE."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vorstellung",src:"the introduction, the idea",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Vor + Stellung (position).\nMeans both 'introduction' and 'imagination.'",example:"A: Haben Sie eine Vorstellung vom Gehalt?\nB: Ja, ich habe eine klare Vorstellung.\nA: Gut. Dann lassen Sie uns darüber sprechen.\nB: Gern.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have an idea about the salary?\nB: Yes, I have a clear idea.\nA: Good. Then let us talk about it.\nB: Gladly.",funFact:"'Hast du eine Vorstellung?' can mean 'Do you have an idea?' or 'Do you have an appointment?' Literally 'placing yourself before someone.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Vorstellungsgespräch",src:"the job interview",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Vorstellung + Gespräch (conversation).\nThe formal German word for job interview.",example:"A: Wann ist Ihr Vorstellungsgespräch?\nB: Am Dienstag um zehn Uhr.\nA: Sind Sie nervös?\nB: Ein bisschen. Aber ich bin gut vorbereitet.",exampleSrc:"A: When is your job interview?\nB: On Tuesday at ten o'clock.\nA: Are you nervous?\nB: A little. But I am well prepared.",funFact:"A 'getting-to-know-you conversation.' Das Vorstellungsgespräch is always neuter because Gespräch is the last element. The gender of the last word in a compound always wins."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wann ist Ihr Vorstellungsgespräch? Was ist ein Vorstellungsgespräch?",opts:["a presentation","a job interview","a company meeting","a phone call"],ans:"a job interview",hint:"Vorstellung + Gespräch. A formal conversation where you introduce yourself to a potential employer."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l1b",title:"Der rote Stift (Teil 2)",icon:"🖊️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der rote Stift (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Unterlage",src:"the document, the paperwork",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Often used in plural: die Unterlagen.\nDocuments needed for applications and official processes.",example:"A: Haben Sie alle Unterlagen?\nB: Ja, hier ist alles.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have all the documents?\nB: Yes, everything is here.",funFact:"From 'unter' (under) + 'Lage' (position/layer). Literally documents you lay under consideration. In job applications, 'Bewerbungsunterlagen' is the standard term for the full application package."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bereit",src:"ready",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Bist du bereit?' = Are you ready?\nRelated to 'bereiten' (to prepare).",example:"A: Bist du bereit für das Gespräch?\nB: Ja, ich bin bereit.\nA: Hast du alle Unterlagen?\nB: Ja. Lebenslauf, Zeugnisse, alles.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you ready for the interview?\nB: Yes, I am ready.\nA: Do you have all the documents?\nB: Yes. CV, certificates, everything.",funFact:"'Bist du bereit?' is what coaches, teachers, and mentors ask before the big moment. Ready means you have prepared. Being 'bereit' is a state you earned."},
{type:"teach",trg:"korrekt",src:"correct, fair",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Same as English 'correct.' From Latin 'correctus.'\nAlso means 'fair/decent' in slang.",example:"A: Sind alle Angaben korrekt?\nB: Ja, alles ist korrekt.\nA: Gut. Dann schicken wir die Bewerbung ab.\nB: Perfekt. Vielen Dank für Ihre Hilfe.",exampleSrc:"A: Is all the information correct?\nB: Yes, everything is correct.\nA: Good. Then we will send off the application.\nB: Perfect. Thank you very much for your help.",funFact:"In German, korrekt also means 'fair/decent' in slang: 'Er ist ein korrekter Typ' (He is a decent guy). Double meaning: accurate AND upstanding."},
{type:"teach",trg:"persönlich",src:"personal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Person + -lich.\n'Persönliche Daten' = personal data.",example:"A: Bitte tragen Sie Ihre persönlichen Daten ein.\nB: Name, Adresse, Geburtsdatum?\nA: Ja, und Familienstand.\nB: Verstanden.",exampleSrc:"A: Please enter your personal data.\nB: Name, address, date of birth?\nA: Yes, and marital status.\nB: Understood.",funFact:"Your persönliche Daten go on every German form. In job interviews, persönliche Fragen about family or religion are actually illegal to ask."},
{type:"teach",trg:"höflich",src:"polite",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Hof' (court). Being höflich originally meant\nbehaving like someone at a royal court.",example:"A: War der Interviewer nett?\nB: Ja, sehr höflich und professionell.\nA: Das ist wichtig. Sei auch du höflich.\nB: Natürlich. Immer höflich und freundlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the interviewer nice?\nB: Yes, very polite and professional.\nA: That is important. Be polite too.\nB: Of course. Always polite and friendly.",funFact:"From 'Hof' (court). Being höflich originally meant behaving like someone at a royal court. Courtly manners became 'polite.' Same etymology as English 'courteous' from 'court.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Bist du {1} für das Vorstellungsgespräch?",a:["bereit"],opts:["bereit","korrekt","persönlich","höflich"],hint:"The state of being fully prepared and able to start immediately. Not nervous, just confident.",sSrc:"Are you ready for the job interview?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"erstellen",src:"to create, to produce",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Er- + stellen (to place).\nMore formal than 'machen.' The professional word.",example:"A: Können Sie einen Bericht erstellen?\nB: Ja, ich erstelle ihn bis Freitag.\nA: Gut. Bitte erstellen Sie auch eine Übersicht.\nB: Kein Problem.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you create a report?\nB: Yes, I will create it by Friday.\nA: Good. Please also create an overview.\nB: No problem.",funFact:"You 'erstellen' a document, report, or CV. More formal than 'machen.' The professional word for creation. Er- + stellen: to make something stand."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erwarten",src:"to expect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Er- + warten (to wait).\nTo expect is to 'wait out' for something.",example:"A: Was erwarten Sie von diesem Job?\nB: Ich erwarte gute Arbeitsbedingungen.\nA: Und was können wir von Ihnen erwarten?\nB: Engagement und Zuverlässigkeit.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you expect from this job?\nB: I expect good working conditions.\nA: And what can we expect from you?\nB: Commitment and reliability.",funFact:"'Was erwarten Sie von diesem Job?' is a classic interview question. To expect is literally to 'wait out' for something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reagieren",src:"to react",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. From Latin 're-agere' (to act back).\nSame word in English, French, and German.",example:"A: Wie reagieren Sie auf Kritik?\nB: Ich nehme Kritik ernst und lerne daraus.\nA: Gut. Und wie reagieren Sie unter Stress?\nB: Ich bleibe ruhig und fokussiert.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you react to criticism?\nB: I take criticism seriously and learn from it.\nA: Good. And how do you react under stress?\nB: I stay calm and focused.",funFact:"'Wie reagieren Sie auf Kritik?' (How do you react to criticism?) is another classic interview question. From Latin 're-agere' (to act back)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort passt? 'In Deutschland ist eine Bewerbung ein ___ Dokument.'",opts:["höfliches","persönliches","offizielles","korrektes"],ans:"offizielles",hint:"Dr. Yilmaz emphasized that a German application has formal, official status."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Frist",src:"the deadline",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. A time limit for completing something.\n'Die Frist endet am...' = The deadline ends on...",example:"A: Wann ist die Frist?\nB: Am fünfzehnten März.",exampleSrc:"A: When is the deadline?\nB: On the fifteenth of March.",funFact:"From Old High German 'frist' (respite, delay). A Frist is the time you are given to act. Missing a Frist in German bureaucracy can have serious consequences."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beachten",src:"to observe, to pay attention to",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Be- + achten (to regard).\n'Bitte beachten Sie die Regeln.'",example:"A: Bitte beachten Sie die Frist.\nB: Wann ist die Frist?\nA: Am fünfzehnten März.\nB: Gut, ich beachte das. Vielen Dank.",exampleSrc:"A: Please observe the deadline.\nB: When is the deadline?\nA: On the fifteenth of March.\nB: Good, I will note that. Thank you.",funFact:"Achtung + be- prefix = active attention. 'Bitte beachten Sie die Regeln' (Please observe the rules). To beachten is to actively pay attention, not just to notice passively."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie heißt der Satz 'Ohne Vorbereitung kein Erfolg' auf Englisch?",opts:["Without success no preparation","Without preparation no success","Without impression no career","Without career no success (formal)"],ans:"Without preparation no success",hint:"Vorbereitung means getting ready before an event. Erfolg means the positive result."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anfangs",src:"at first, initially",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"From Anfang (beginning). The -s ending turns\nit into an adverb.",example:"A: Wie war der erste Tag?\nB: Anfangs war ich sehr nervös.\nA: Und jetzt?\nB: Jetzt fühle ich mich sicher.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the first day?\nB: At first I was very nervous.\nA: And now?\nB: Now I feel confident.",funFact:"'Anfangs war ich nervös' (At first I was nervous). Perfect for telling the story of how you started somewhere. The -s ending turns the noun Anfang into an adverb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"per",src:"by, via",pos:"prep",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'per' (through/by means of).\n'Per E-Mail,' 'per Post.' Formal usage.",example:"A: Wie schicke ich die Bewerbung?\nB: Per E-Mail oder per Post.\nA: Was ist besser?\nB: Die meisten Firmen bevorzugen per E-Mail.",exampleSrc:"A: How do I send the application?\nB: By email or by mail.\nA: What is better?\nB: Most companies prefer by email.",funFact:"'Per E-Mail' (by email), 'per Post' (by mail). Short, efficient, and used in formal writing. German borrowed it directly from Latin and never let go."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Bewerbung",src:"application"},{trg:"Lebenslauf",src:"CV/resume"},{trg:"Erfolg",src:"success"},{trg:"Karriere",src:"career"},{trg:"Eindruck",src:"impression"},{trg:"Vorbereitung",src:"preparation"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-vhs-office",trg:"Für morgen: schreib deinen Lebenslauf neu. Auf Deutsch. Jede Zeile. Und dann zeigst du ihn mir.",src:"For tomorrow: rewrite your CV. In German. Every line. And then you show it to me."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Unterlage'?",opts:["the impression","the application","to create, to produce","the document, the paperwork"],ans:"the document, the paperwork",hint:"Unter (under) + Lage (layer/position). Papers that support your case."},
{type:"fb",s:"Was {1} Sie von diesem Job?",a:["erwarten"],opts:["das Vorstellungsgespräch","erstellen","erwarten","die Unterlage"],hint:"A verb meaning 'to anticipate' or 'to look forward to'. Er- prefix + warten (to wait).",sSrc:"What do you expect from this job?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'reagieren'?",opts:["the CV, the resume","personal","to react","to expect"],ans:"to react",hint:"Almost identical to the English cognate. Latin re- (back) + agere (to act)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wann ist {1}?",a:["die Frist"],opts:["die Frist","korrekt","die Vorstellung","der Eindruck"],hint:"A feminine noun for a time limit. From Old High German meaning a set period of respite.",sSrc:"When is the deadline?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'beachten'?",opts:["the job interview","the preparation","the application","to observe, to pay attention to"],ans:"to observe, to pay attention to",hint:"Be- prefix + achten (to respect/heed). To heed or notice something with care."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 2: Berufe und Qualifikationen ====================
{id:"deu_r13l2",title:"Berufe und Qualifikationen",icon:"🎓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Berufe und Qualifikationen",desc:"Learn vocabulary for professions and qualifications. Understand the German training system. Master masculine/feminine job title pairs.",goals:["Name professions and qualifications","Understand the German training system","Master masculine/feminine job title pairs"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Yilmaz legt einen Stapel Stellenanzeigen vor Verumius auf den Tisch. Ingenieur, Lehrerin, Mechatroniker. Jeder Beruf hat seine eigene Sprache.",src:"Yilmaz places a stack of job listings in front of Verumius on the table. Engineer, teacher, mechatronics technician. Every profession has its own language."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Qualifikation",src:"the qualification",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Same Latin root as English.\nGerman job ads list Qualifikationen precisely.",example:"A: Welche Qualifikationen haben Sie?\nB: Ich habe einen Master in Informatik.\nA: Und welche praktischen Qualifikationen?\nB: Drei Jahre Erfahrung als Entwickler.",exampleSrc:"A: What qualifications do you have?\nB: I have a Master's in computer science.\nA: And what practical qualifications?\nB: Three years of experience as a developer.",funFact:"German job ads list Qualifikationen more precisely than most countries. They expect you to prove every single one with a certificate or reference."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fähigkeit",src:"the ability, the skill",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'fähig' (capable) + '-keit.'\n'Soziale Fähigkeiten' = social skills.",example:"A: Welche Fähigkeiten bringen Sie mit?\nB: Ich bin gut im Teamwork.\nA: Haben Sie technische Fähigkeiten?\nB: Ja, ich kann programmieren.",exampleSrc:"A: What skills do you bring?\nB: I am good at teamwork.\nA: Do you have technical skills?\nB: Yes, I can program.",funFact:"'Soziale Fähigkeiten' (social skills) appear on every German job listing. The -keit ending always makes feminine nouns. Fähig (capable) becomes Fähigkeit (capability)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fortbildung",src:"the continuing education",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Fort (further) + Bildung (education).\nProfessional development.",example:"A: Waren Sie auf einer Fortbildung?\nB: Ja, letzte Woche. Projektmanagement.\nA: Gut. Fortbildung ist uns wichtig.\nB: Mir auch. Ich lerne gern Neues.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you attend continuing education?\nB: Yes, last week. Project management.\nA: Good. Continuing education is important to us.\nB: To me too. I like learning new things.",funFact:"Germans take Fortbildung seriously. Many employers pay for it. It shows you never stop learning. Fort (further/onward) + Bildung (education)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Weiterbildung",src:"the further education",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Weiter (further) + Bildung (education).\nBroader than Fortbildung.",example:"A: Planen Sie eine Weiterbildung?\nB: Ja, ich möchte Spanisch lernen.\nA: Beruflich oder privat?\nB: Beides. Weiterbildung ist immer gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you planning further education?\nB: Yes, I would like to learn Spanish.\nA: Professionally or privately?\nB: Both. Further education is always good.",funFact:"Nearly synonymous with Fortbildung but broader. Weiterbildung can be personal growth too, not just professional. Both are feminine because of Bildung."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Welche Fähigkeiten bringen Sie mit?' Was bedeutet Fähigkeit?",opts:["certificate","qualification","ability/skill","education"],ans:"ability/skill",hint:"From the adjective 'fähig' (capable). The -keit ending turns it into a noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Zertifikat",src:"the certificate",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'certificare' (to make certain).\nGermans love certificates.",example:"A: Haben Sie ein Zertifikat?\nB: Ja, ein B2-Zertifikat in Deutsch.\nA: Sehr gut. Das brauchen wir.\nB: Hier ist die Kopie.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a certificate?\nB: Yes, a B2 certificate in German.\nA: Very good. We need that.\nB: Here is the copy.",funFact:"Germans love certificates. You can get a Zertifikat for almost anything: language level, first aid, fire safety, even coffee brewing. Das Zertifikat is always neuter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Diplom",src:"the diploma",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Greek 'diploma' (folded paper).\nThe traditional German university degree.",example:"A: Haben Sie ein Diplom?\nB: Ja, ein Diplom in Maschinenbau.\nA: Von welcher Universität?\nB: Von der TU München.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a diploma?\nB: Yes, a diploma in mechanical engineering.\nA: From which university?\nB: From the TU Munich.",funFact:"Das Diplom was the traditional German university degree before the Bologna reform. Some older Germans still proudly use 'Diplom-Ingenieur' as a title."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Abitur",src:"the high school leaving exam",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'abire' (to go away).\nWithout it, university is nearly impossible.",example:"A: Hast du Abitur?\nB: Ja, mit der Note 1,8.\nA: Sehr gut! Was hast du dann studiert?\nB: Informatik in Berlin.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have the Abitur?\nB: Yes, with a grade of 1.8.\nA: Very good! What did you study then?\nB: Computer science in Berlin.",funFact:"Das Abitur is the German high school leaving exam. It takes 12 to 13 years of schooling to reach. The equivalent of A-levels or SATs but considerably harder."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich habe ein {1} in Projektmanagement.",a:["Zertifikat"],opts:["Zertifikat","Diplom","Abitur","Abschluss"],hint:"A neuter noun from Latin meaning a document certifying you completed a course.",sSrc:"I have a certificate in project management."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Abschluss",src:"the degree, the completion",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Ab (off) + Schluss (closing).\n'Welchen Abschluss haben Sie?'",example:"A: Welchen Abschluss haben Sie?\nB: Einen Bachelor in Wirtschaft.\nA: Und planen Sie einen weiteren Abschluss?\nB: Ja, einen Master.",exampleSrc:"A: What degree do you have?\nB: A Bachelor's in economics.\nA: And are you planning another degree?\nB: Yes, a Master's.",funFact:"'Welchen Abschluss haben Sie?' is a standard interview question. The word implies you closed a chapter of your education. Ab (off) + Schluss (closing)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lehre",src:"the apprenticeship",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'lehren' (to teach).\nGermany's famous dual education system.",example:"A: Hast du eine Lehre gemacht?\nB: Ja, als Elektriker. Drei Jahre.\nA: Wo war die Lehre?\nB: Bei Bosch in Stuttgart.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you do an apprenticeship?\nB: Yes, as an electrician. Three years.\nA: Where was the apprenticeship?\nB: At Bosch in Stuttgart.",funFact:"Die Lehre is Germany's famous dual education system: you work at a company AND attend school. Fifty percent of Germans do a Lehre instead of university."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Lehrling",src:"the apprentice",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Lehre + -ling (person suffix).\nThe -ling suffix has a junior quality.",example:"A: Wie viele Lehrlinge habt ihr?\nB: Dieses Jahr fünf neue Lehrlinge.\nA: In welchem Bereich?\nB: Drei in der IT, zwei im Marketing.",exampleSrc:"A: How many apprentices do you have?\nB: This year five new apprentices.\nA: In which field?\nB: Three in IT, two in marketing.",funFact:"The -ling suffix often has a diminutive or junior quality: Lehrling (apprentice), Frühling (spring, the 'young' season). Always masculine grammatically."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lehrstelle",src:"the apprenticeship position",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Lehre + Stelle (position).\nFinding one is a big deal for teenagers.",example:"A: Hast du schon eine Lehrstelle gefunden?\nB: Nein, ich suche noch.\nA: Bewirb dich bei Siemens.\nB: Gute Idee. Die haben viele Lehrstellen.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you found an apprenticeship position yet?\nB: No, I am still looking.\nA: Apply at Siemens.\nB: Good idea. They have many positions.",funFact:"Finding a Lehrstelle is a big deal for German teenagers. Companies compete for good Lehrlinge, and Lehrlinge compete for good Lehrstellen."},
{type:"mc",q:"Hast du eine Lehre gemacht? Was ist eine Lehre?",opts:["a university degree","an apprenticeship","a certificate","a job interview"],ans:"an apprenticeship",hint:"Germany's famous dual education system where you work at a company AND attend school."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l2b",title:"Berufe und Qualifikationen (Teil 2)",icon:"🎓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Berufe und Qualifikationen (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Praktikant",src:"the intern (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'Praktikum' + '-ant.'\nThe -ant ending signals a person doing something.",example:"A: Der neue Praktikant fängt morgen an.\nB: Wie lange bleibt er?\nA: Drei Monate.\nB: Gut. Ich zeige ihm alles.",exampleSrc:"A: The new intern starts tomorrow.\nB: How long will he stay?\nA: Three months.\nB: Good. I will show him everything.",funFact:"The -ant ending comes from Latin and always signals a person doing something. Always masculine. From Praktikum (internship)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Praktikantin",src:"the intern (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Praktikant + '-in.'\nThe -in suffix is the universal feminine marker.",example:"A: Unsere Praktikantin ist sehr fleißig.\nB: Ja, sie arbeitet hervorragend.\nA: Vielleicht stellen wir sie ein.\nB: Das wäre toll für sie.",exampleSrc:"A: Our intern is very diligent.\nB: Yes, she works excellently.\nA: Maybe we will hire her.\nB: That would be great for her.",funFact:"German always has masculine/feminine pairs for professions. The -in suffix is the universal feminine marker. Always die."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ingenieur",src:"the engineer",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From French 'ingénieur.'\nA title of respect in Germany.",example:"A: Was ist Ihr Beruf?\nB: Ich bin Ingenieur.\nA: In welchem Bereich?\nB: Maschinenbau. Seit zehn Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your profession?\nB: I am an engineer.\nA: In which field?\nB: Mechanical engineering. For ten years.",funFact:"Germany is famous for engineering. 'Made in Germany' was originally a British warning label. Germans turned it into a badge of pride. Der Ingenieur is a title of respect."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Architekt",src:"the architect (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From Greek 'architekton' (master builder).\nRequires university degree and state registration.",example:"A: Wer hat dieses Gebäude entworfen?\nB: Ein bekannter Architekt aus Berlin.\nA: Es ist wunderschön.\nB: Ja, der Architekt hat viele Preise gewonnen.",exampleSrc:"A: Who designed this building?\nB: A well-known architect from Berlin.\nA: It is beautiful.\nB: Yes, the architect has won many awards.",funFact:"Germany's Bauhaus movement revolutionized architecture worldwide. German architects are required to have a university degree and state registration."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Architektin",src:"the architect (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Architekt + '-in.'\nThe -in suffix works on every profession.",example:"A: Die Architektin hat den Plan geändert.\nB: Warum?\nA: Das Dach war zu flach.\nB: Sie hat recht. Sicherheit geht vor.",exampleSrc:"A: The architect changed the plan.\nB: Why?\nA: The roof was too flat.\nB: She is right. Safety comes first.",funFact:"The -in suffix works on every profession: Lehrer/Lehrerin, Arzt/Ärztin, Architekt/Architektin. Once you know the pattern, you can feminize any profession."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die neue {1} fängt morgen an. Sie bleibt drei Monate.",a:["Praktikantin"],opts:["Praktikantin","Ingenieurin","Architektin","Lehrerin"],hint:"A woman doing unpaid or low-paid work experience at a company. Germany requires many of these for degree programs.",sSrc:"The new intern starts tomorrow. She stays three months."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Mechaniker",src:"the mechanic (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From Greek 'mechanikos.'\nRequires a 3.5-year apprenticeship in Germany.",example:"A: Mein Auto ist kaputt.\nB: Bring es zum Mechaniker.\nA: Kennst du einen guten Mechaniker?\nB: Ja, in der Hauptstraße. Sehr gut.",exampleSrc:"A: My car is broken.\nB: Take it to the mechanic.\nA: Do you know a good mechanic?\nB: Yes, on the main street. Very good.",funFact:"In Germany, a Mechaniker must complete a 3.5-year apprenticeship. German car mechanics are among the best trained in the world because of this system."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mechanikerin",src:"the mechanic (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Mechaniker + '-in.'\nMore women enter traditionally male professions.",example:"A: Die Mechanikerin hat mein Auto repariert.\nB: War sie gut?\nA: Ausgezeichnet. Schnell und professionell.\nB: Gut zu wissen.",exampleSrc:"A: The mechanic repaired my car.\nB: Was she good?\nA: Excellent. Fast and professional.\nB: Good to know.",funFact:"More and more women enter traditionally male professions in Germany. The language always had the feminine form ready."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beruflich",src:"professional, work-related",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Beruf (profession) + -lich.\n'Beruflich läuft es gut' = Professionally, things are going well.",example:"A: Wie läuft es beruflich?\nB: Gut. Ich habe eine Beförderung bekommen.\nA: Glückwunsch! Und privat?\nB: Auch gut. Alles in Balance.",exampleSrc:"A: How are things going professionally?\nB: Good. I got a promotion.\nA: Congratulations! And personally?\nB: Also good. Everything in balance.",funFact:"The -lich suffix turns nouns into adjectives, like English '-ly.' Beruf (profession) becomes beruflich (professional). Freund becomes freundlich (friendly)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"berufstätig",src:"employed, working",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Beruf + tätig (active/engaged).\n'Sind Sie berufstätig?' = Are you employed?",example:"A: Sind Sie berufstätig?\nB: Ja, ich arbeite als Lehrerin.\nA: Vollzeit oder Teilzeit?\nB: Vollzeit. Vierzig Stunden pro Woche.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you employed?\nB: Yes, I work as a teacher.\nA: Full-time or part-time?\nB: Full-time. Forty hours per week.",funFact:"'Sind Sie berufstätig?' (Are you employed?) is a standard form question. Being berufstätig is a core part of German identity."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ingenieurin",src:"the engineer (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine of Ingenieur. Ingenieur + '-in.'\nThe -in suffix works on every profession.",example:"A: Die Ingenieurin hat den Plan erstellt.\nB: Welche Ingenieurin?\nA: Frau Dr. Braun. Sie arbeitet bei Siemens.\nB: Eine erfahrene Ingenieurin.",exampleSrc:"A: The engineer created the plan.\nB: Which engineer?\nA: Dr. Braun. She works at Siemens.\nB: An experienced engineer.",funFact:"Germany has seen a steady increase in female engineers. The -in suffix applies to every profession: Ingenieur/Ingenieurin, just like Lehrer/Lehrerin."},
{type:"tip",title:"Das deutsche -in-Muster",text:"Every masculine profession has a feminine form: add -in.\n\nLehrer / Lehrerin (teacher)\nIngenieur / Ingenieurin (engineer)\nArchitekt / Architektin (architect)\nMechaniker / Mechanikerin (mechanic)\n\nThe plural feminizes too:\nLehrerinnen, Architektinnen\n\nModern German increasingly uses gender-neutral forms:\nArchitekt*innen or Ingenieur:innen\n\nYou will see all variants in job listings and official documents.",deepDive:{title:"N-Deklination bei Berufen",text:"Some masculine profession nouns follow the n-Deklination. They add -n or -en in all cases except nominative singular.\n\nder Architekt, den Architekten, dem Architekten\nder Kandidat, den Kandidaten, dem Kandidaten\nder Praktikant, den Praktikanten, dem Praktikanten\n\nClues: masculine nouns ending in -ent, -ant, -ist, -at, or -e often follow this pattern."}},
{type:"mc",q:"A female engineer in German is...",opts:["Ingenieur","Architektin","Ingenieurin","Mechanikerin"],ans:"Ingenieurin",hint:"Take the masculine profession word for engineer and add the feminine suffix."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Abitur",src:"high school exam"},{trg:"Lehre",src:"apprenticeship"},{trg:"Diplom",src:"university degree"},{trg:"Zertifikat",src:"certificate"},{trg:"Abschluss",src:"degree/completion"},{trg:"Fortbildung",src:"continuing education"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Nach dem Studium hat sie einen {1} in Informatik.",a:["Abschluss"],opts:["Abschluss","Anfang","Lehrling","Praktikant"],hint:"The word for completing your education, literally a 'closing off.'",sSrc:"After her studies she has a degree in computer science."},
{type:"mc",q:"Weiterbildung means...",opts:["university degree","continuing education","apprenticeship","job interview"],ans:"continuing education",hint:"Break the compound word into its two parts: one means going on or onward, the other refers to developing knowledge and skills."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Architekt'?",opts:["the degree, the completion","professional, work-related","the architect (male)","the qualification"],ans:"the architect (male)",hint:"A direct Greek/Latin cognate. The person who designs buildings."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'the mechanic (male)' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["der Mechaniker"],opts:["der Mechaniker","das Abitur","die Fortbildung","die Fähigkeit"],hint:"A Latin/Greek cognate with -iker ending. The person who repairs machines.",sSrc:"How do you say 'the mechanic (male)' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'berufstätig'?",opts:["the degree, the completion","the diploma","the high school leaving exam","employed, working"],ans:"employed, working",hint:"Beruf (profession) + tätig (active/doing). Actively engaged in a profession."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 3: Persönliche Angaben ====================
{id:"deu_r13l3",title:"Persönliche Angaben",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Persönliche Angaben",desc:"Learn essential CV documentation vocabulary. Master nouns for qualifications, reports, and employment. Build your professional German word bank.",goals:["Learn essential CV documentation vocabulary","Master nouns for qualifications and reports","Build your professional German word bank"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Für den Lebenslauf brauchst du das Präteritum. Nicht 'Ich habe studiert,' sondern 'Ich studierte.' Das klingt professioneller.",src:"For the CV you need the Präteritum. Not 'I have studied,' but 'I studied.' That sounds more professional."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thinking",trg:"Also: 'Ich studierte Linguistik in Istanbul. Ich arbeitete drei Jahre als Übersetzer.' So?",src:"So: 'I studied linguistics in Istanbul. I worked three years as a translator.' Like that?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"pleased",trg:"Genau! Und bei starken Verben ändert sich der Vokal: 'Ich schrieb,' nicht 'Ich schreibte.' Das musst du lernen.",src:"Exactly! And with strong verbs the vowel changes: 'Ich schrieb,' not 'Ich schreibte.' You need to learn that."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Angabe",src:"the information, the detail",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. An (at) + Gabe (giving).\n'Persönliche Angaben' = personal details on a CV.",example:"A: Sind alle Angaben korrekt?\nB: Ja, ich habe alles überprüft.\nA: Gut. Falsche Angaben können Probleme verursachen.\nB: Ich weiß. Alles ist korrekt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is all the information correct?\nB: Yes, I checked everything.\nA: Good. False information can cause problems.\nB: I know. Everything is correct.",funFact:"'Persönliche Angaben' is the first section on every German CV. Die Angabe is always feminine because of the -e ending from Gabe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Personalie",src:"the personal detail",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Usually plural: Personalien.\n'Personalien aufnehmen' = to take down details.",example:"A: Bitte geben Sie Ihre Personalien an.\nB: Name, Adresse, Geburtsdatum?\nA: Ja, und Ihren Familienstand.\nB: Ledig. Hier sind meine Personalien.",exampleSrc:"A: Please state your personal details.\nB: Name, address, date of birth?\nA: Yes, and your marital status.\nB: Single. Here are my details.",funFact:"'Personalien aufnehmen' is what police do when they take down your details. On a CV, your Personalien include name, address, and date of birth."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Personenstand",src:"the marital status",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Personen + Stand (status).\nLedig (single), verheiratet (married).",example:"A: Wie ist Ihr Personenstand?\nB: Ich bin ledig.\nA: Das gehört auf den Lebenslauf?\nB: Traditionell ja, aber es ist freiwillig.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your marital status?\nB: I am single.\nA: Does that go on the CV?\nB: Traditionally yes, but it is voluntary.",funFact:"German CVs traditionally include marital status. Many modern career advisors now recommend leaving it out. Ledig (single), verheiratet (married)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Personal",src:"the staff, the personnel",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'personalis.'\n'Die Personalabteilung' = HR department.",example:"A: Haben Sie genug Personal?\nB: Nein, wir brauchen mehr Personal.\nA: In welcher Abteilung?\nB: Im Kundenservice. Fünf neue Stellen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have enough staff?\nB: No, we need more staff.\nA: In which department?\nB: In customer service. Five new positions.",funFact:"'Die Personalabteilung' (HR department) handles your Bewerbung. Das Personal is neuter and collective. One word for all the people who work somewhere."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Bitte geben Sie Ihre Personalien an.' Was sind Personalien?",opts:["personal opinions","personal details","personal belongings","personal goals"],ans:"personal details",hint:"Name, address, date of birth. What police take down or what goes at the top of your CV."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Empfehlung",src:"the recommendation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'empfehlen' (to recommend).\n'Empfehlungsschreiben' = letter of recommendation.",example:"A: Haben Sie eine Empfehlung?\nB: Ja, von meinem früheren Chef.\nA: Gut. Eine gute Empfehlung hilft sehr.\nB: Hier ist das Schreiben.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a recommendation?\nB: Yes, from my former boss.\nA: Good. A good recommendation helps a lot.\nB: Here is the letter.",funFact:"'Empfehlungsschreiben' (letter of recommendation) is a standard part of German job applications. Germans value written Empfehlungen highly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bericht",src:"the report",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'berichten' (to report).\nArbeitsbericht, Jahresbericht.",example:"A: Der Bericht ist fertig.\nB: Gut. Wie lang ist er?\nA: Zehn Seiten. Mit Grafiken.\nB: Perfekt. Schicken Sie ihn per E-Mail.",exampleSrc:"A: The report is finished.\nB: Good. How long is it?\nA: Ten pages. With graphics.\nB: Perfect. Send it by email.",funFact:"'Arbeitsbericht' (work report), 'Jahresbericht' (annual report). Der Bericht is always masculine. Germans document everything in writing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bereich",src:"the field, the area",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Be- + Reich (realm/area).\n'In welchem Bereich arbeiten Sie?'",example:"A: In welchem Bereich arbeiten Sie?\nB: Im IT-Bereich.\nA: Und in welchem Fachbereich genau?\nB: Softwareentwicklung.",exampleSrc:"A: In which field do you work?\nB: In the IT field.\nA: And in which specialty exactly?\nB: Software development.",funFact:"'In welchem Bereich arbeiten Sie?' (In which field do you work?) is a networking question. Der Bereich covers everything from 'Fachbereich' (department) to 'Lebensbereich' (area of life)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Beitrag",src:"the contribution",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Bei- (alongside) + Trag (carrying).\nAlso means 'fee' in some contexts.",example:"A: Jeder Mitarbeiter leistet einen Beitrag.\nB: Was ist mein Beitrag?\nA: Ihre Sprachkenntnisse. Das ist sehr wertvoll.\nB: Danke. Ich gebe mein Bestes.",exampleSrc:"A: Every employee makes a contribution.\nB: What is my contribution?\nA: Your language skills. That is very valuable.\nB: Thank you. I will do my best.",funFact:"'Einen Beitrag leisten' (to make a contribution) is formal language for doing your part. Also means 'fee' in contexts like 'Mitgliedsbeitrag' (membership fee)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich habe eine gute {1} von meinem früheren Chef.",a:["Empfehlung"],opts:["Empfehlung","Angabe","Bereich","Bedingung"],hint:"A written endorsement from your former employer. It vouches for your character and professional ability.",sSrc:"I have a good recommendation from my former boss."},
{type:"mc",q:"Jeder Mitarbeiter leistet einen ___ zum Projekt.",opts:["Beitrag","Bericht","Bereich","Bedarf"],ans:"Beitrag",hint:"This masculine noun means a contribution or a share of work someone provides."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l3b",title:"Persönliche Angaben (Teil 2)",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Persönliche Angaben (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Beschäftigung",src:"the employment, the occupation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'beschäftigen' (to employ).\nThe -ung ending always makes feminine nouns.",example:"A: Was ist Ihre aktuelle Beschäftigung?\nB: Ich bin als Übersetzer beschäftigt.\nA: Vollzeit?\nB: Ja, seit zwei Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your current occupation?\nB: I am employed as a translator.\nA: Full-time?\nB: Yes, for two years.",funFact:"'Beschäftigungsverhältnis' (employment relationship) is a word that only German bureaucracy could produce. Die Beschäftigung is feminine because of the -ung ending."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bedingung",src:"the condition, the requirement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'bedingen' (to require).\n'Arbeitsbedingungen' = working conditions.",example:"A: Wie sind die Arbeitsbedingungen?\nB: Gut. Flexible Zeiten und Homeoffice.\nA: Unter welchen Bedingungen arbeiten Sie?\nB: Ich brauche mindestens 30 Urlaubstage.",exampleSrc:"A: How are the working conditions?\nB: Good. Flexible hours and home office.\nA: Under what conditions do you work?\nB: I need at least 30 vacation days.",funFact:"'Arbeitsbedingungen' (working conditions) matter in every job. The -ung ending always makes feminine nouns. German workers are protected by strict labor laws."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Bedarf",src:"the need, the demand",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'bedürfen' (to require).\n'Bei Bedarf' = if needed/on demand.",example:"A: Gibt es Bedarf an Übersetzern?\nB: Ja, der Bedarf ist groß.\nA: In welchen Sprachen?\nB: Besonders Türkisch und Arabisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a need for translators?\nB: Yes, the demand is great.\nA: In which languages?\nB: Especially Turkish and Arabic.",funFact:"'Bei Bedarf' (if needed/on demand) appears in contracts and job ads. Der Bedarf is always masculine. The professional way to say 'if you need it.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Anspruch",src:"the claim, the entitlement",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. An + Spruch (saying/claim).\n'Anspruch auf Urlaub' = entitlement to vacation.",example:"A: Habe ich Anspruch auf Urlaub?\nB: Ja, mindestens zwanzig Tage.\nA: Und Anspruch auf Weiterbildung?\nB: Ja, fünf Tage pro Jahr.",exampleSrc:"A: Do I have a right to vacation?\nB: Yes, at least twenty days.\nA: And a right to continuing education?\nB: Yes, five days per year.",funFact:"German workers have strong Ansprüche by law: minimum 20 vacation days, health insurance, parental leave. 'Anspruch auf Urlaub' is a legal entitlement."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Werk",src:"the work, the factory",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Cognate with English 'work.'\nDas Werk von Goethe, Automobilwerk.",example:"A: In welchem Werk arbeiten Sie?\nB: Im Volkswagen-Werk in Wolfsburg.\nA: Wie groß ist das Werk?\nB: Über 60.000 Mitarbeiter.",exampleSrc:"A: In which factory do you work?\nB: In the Volkswagen factory in Wolfsburg.\nA: How big is the factory?\nB: Over 60,000 employees.",funFact:"'Das Werk von Goethe' (the works of Goethe), 'Automobilwerk' (car factory). Cognate with English 'work.' Different from 'Arbeit' (labor). Das Werk is neuter."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Bei Bedarf kontaktieren Sie uns.' Was bedeutet 'bei Bedarf'?",opts:["at the beginning","at the deadline","if needed","at the end"],ans:"if needed",hint:"Der Bedarf means the need or demand. The phrase means 'on demand' or 'if required.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"erfolgreich",src:"successful",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Erfolg (success) + reich (rich).\n'Eine erfolgreiche Bewerbung' = a successful application.",example:"A: War die Bewerbung erfolgreich?\nB: Ja! Ich habe die Stelle bekommen.\nA: Herzlichen Glückwunsch! Du bist erfolgreich.\nB: Danke. Die Vorbereitung hat geholfen.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the application successful?\nB: Yes! I got the job.\nA: Congratulations! You are successful.\nB: Thanks. The preparation helped.",funFact:"Literally 'rich in success.' The -reich suffix means 'rich in' or 'full of.' 'Eine erfolgreiche Bewerbung' is what everyone hopes for."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erforderlich",src:"required, necessary",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'erfordern' (to require).\nMore formal than 'nötig' (needed).",example:"A: Welche Dokumente sind erforderlich?\nB: Lebenslauf, Anschreiben und Zeugnisse.\nA: Ist ein Foto erforderlich?\nB: Nicht mehr, aber es wird empfohlen.",exampleSrc:"A: Which documents are required?\nB: CV, cover letter, and certificates.\nA: Is a photo required?\nB: Not anymore, but it is recommended.",funFact:"'Erforderliche Qualifikationen' appears in every job listing. More formal than 'nötig' (needed). The official language of job ads."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bestimmt",src:"certain, specific, definitely",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'bestimmen' (to determine).\nAlso an adverb: 'Das klappt bestimmt!'",example:"A: Suchen Sie eine bestimmte Stelle?\nB: Ja, im Bereich Übersetzung.\nA: Das klappt bestimmt!\nB: Danke. Ich bin optimistisch.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you looking for a specific position?\nB: Yes, in the translation field.\nA: That will definitely work!\nB: Thanks. I am optimistic.",funFact:"Double function: 'Ein bestimmter Bereich' (a specific area) as adjective. 'Das klappt bestimmt!' (That will definitely work!) as adverb. Context decides."},
{type:"teach",trg:"komplett",src:"complete, entire",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From French 'complet,' from Latin 'completus.'\n'Ihre Bewerbung ist komplett.'",example:"A: Ist meine Bewerbung komplett?\nB: Fast. Es fehlt noch ein Zeugnis.\nA: Welches?\nB: Das Arbeitszeugnis von Ihrer letzten Stelle.",exampleSrc:"A: Is my application complete?\nB: Almost. A certificate is still missing.\nA: Which one?\nB: The work reference from your last position.",funFact:"'Ihre Bewerbung ist komplett' (Your application is complete) is what you want to hear from HR. From French 'complet,' from Latin 'completus.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"offiziell",src:"official",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From French 'officiel,' from Latin 'officium.'\nStress on the last syllable: off-ih-tsee-ELL.",example:"A: Ist das ein offizielles Dokument?\nB: Ja, mit Stempel und Unterschrift.\nA: Gut. Wir brauchen offizielle Unterlagen.\nB: Hier sind alle offiziellen Papiere.",exampleSrc:"A: Is this an official document?\nB: Yes, with stamp and signature.\nA: Good. We need official documents.\nB: Here are all the official papers.",funFact:"Pronounced 'off-ih-tsee-ELL' with stress on the last syllable. German borrowed it with French pronunciation. 'Ein offizielles Dokument' (an official document)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort bedeutet 'recommendation' in a professional context?",opts:["Bedingung","Beschäftigung","Empfehlung","Angabe"],ans:"Empfehlung",hint:"A formal written endorsement submitted with job applications. Your former boss vouches for your skills."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Angabe",src:"information/detail"},{trg:"Bericht",src:"report"},{trg:"Bereich",src:"field/area"},{trg:"Beschäftigung",src:"employment"},{trg:"Bedarf",src:"need/demand"},{trg:"Empfehlung",src:"recommendation"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie ist Ihr {1}? Ledig oder verheiratet?",a:["Personenstand"],opts:["Personenstand","Personal","Personalie","Bereich"],hint:"The formal field on German CVs and official documents asking whether you are single, married, or divorced.",sSrc:"What is your marital status? Single or married?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Bedarf' in einem beruflichen Kontext?",opts:["die Angabe","die Bedingung","der Mangel","die Nachfrage"],ans:"die Nachfrage",hint:"Think of what a company needs. 'Bei Bedarf' means 'if needed' or 'on demand.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Stelle ist {1} ausgeschrieben. Bitte bewerben Sie sich bis Freitag.",a:["offiziell"],opts:["offiziell","komplett","bestimmt","erforderlich"],hint:"The job listing has been formally published in the government gazette or company portal. Applications are now open.",sSrc:"The position is officially posted. Please apply by Friday."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Anspruch'?",opts:["the work, the factory","the claim, the entitlement","required, necessary","certain, specific, definitely"],ans:"the claim, the entitlement",hint:"An- (at/to) + Spruch (saying/verdict). A formal demand or right to something."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie groß ist {1}?",a:["das Werk"],opts:["das Personal","die Beschäftigung","das Werk","erforderlich"],hint:"A neuter noun for a factory or large creative work. Think of major automotive plants.",sSrc:"How big is the factory?"},
{type:"fb",s:"War die Bewerbung {1}? Ja, ich habe die Stelle bekommen!",a:"erfolgreich",opts:["erfolgreich","erforderlich","bestimmt","komplett"],hint:"This adjective means rich in success. Built from Erfolg + reich.",sSrc:"Was the application successful? Yes, I got the job!"}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 4: Ich studierte in Istanbul ====================
{id:"deu_r13l4",title:"Ich studierte in Istanbul",icon:"📜",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ich studierte in Istanbul",desc:"Learn the Präteritum (narrative past tense). Understand strong vs. weak verb patterns. Master wissen vs. kennen.",goals:["Learn the Präteritum (narrative past tense)","Understand strong vs. weak verb patterns","Master wissen vs. kennen"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"angeben",src:"to state, to specify",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + geben (to give).\n'Bitte geben Sie Ihre Adresse an.'",example:"A: Bitte geben Sie Ihre Adresse an.\nB: Hauptstraße 12, 10115 Berlin.\nA: Und Ihre Telefonnummer?\nB: Gebe ich auch an. 030-12345.",exampleSrc:"A: Please state your address.\nB: Main Street 12, 10115 Berlin.\nA: And your phone number?\nB: I will state that too. 030-12345.",funFact:"Separable verb: 'Ich gebe meine Daten an.' Also colloquially means 'to show off.' 'Gib nicht so an!' (Don't show off!). Context matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beschäftigen",src:"to employ, to occupy",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Reflexive: 'sich beschäftigen mit...'\n'Die Firma beschäftigt 200 Mitarbeiter.'",example:"A: Wie viele Leute beschäftigt die Firma?\nB: Etwa 500 Mitarbeiter.\nA: Und womit beschäftigen Sie sich?\nB: Ich beschäftige mich mit Softwareentwicklung.",exampleSrc:"A: How many people does the company employ?\nB: About 500 employees.\nA: And what do you occupy yourself with?\nB: I occupy myself with software development.",funFact:"Two uses: 'Die Firma beschäftigt 200 Mitarbeiter' (The company employs 200 workers). Reflexive: 'Ich beschäftige mich mit...' (I occupy myself with...)."},
{type:"tip",title:"Präteritum: The Narrative Past",text:"Spoken German mostly uses the Perfekt:\nIch habe geschrieben.\n\nBut written German, especially in CVs, uses the Präteritum:\nIch schrieb.\n\nStrong verbs change the vowel:\nschreiben / schrieb, gehen / ging, kommen / kam\n\nWeak verbs add -te:\narbeiten / arbeitete, studieren / studierte\n\nFor sein, haben, and modal verbs, even spoken German uses Präteritum:\nwar, hatte, konnte, musste.",deepDive:{title:"When Präteritum, when Perfekt?",text:"Rule of thumb:\n\nPräteritum in:\n1. CVs and formal texts\n2. Narratives and reports\n3. With sein, haben, modal verbs (always)\n\nPerfekt in:\n1. Everyday conversations\n2. Oral reports\n3. Informal emails\n\n'Ich studierte in Istanbul' sounds more professional than 'Ich habe in Istanbul studiert.' Both are correct, but the CV demands Präteritum."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: Starke Verben",groups:[{label:"Häufige starke Verben",rows:[{pronoun:"gehen",form:"ging",src:"went"},{pronoun:"kommen",form:"kam",src:"came"},{pronoun:"schreiben",form:"schrieb",src:"wrote"},{pronoun:"sprechen",form:"sprach",src:"spoke"},{pronoun:"geben",form:"gab",src:"gave"},{pronoun:"nehmen",form:"nahm",src:"took"},{pronoun:"finden",form:"fand",src:"found"},{pronoun:"stehen",form:"stand",src:"stood"},{pronoun:"lesen",form:"las",src:"read"}]},{label:"Konjugation: schreiben",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"schrieb",src:"I wrote"},{pronoun:"du",form:"schriebst",src:"you wrote"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"schrieb",src:"he/she/it wrote"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"schrieben",src:"we wrote"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"schriebt",src:"you all wrote"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"schrieben",src:"they/you wrote"}]}],note:"Strong verbs change their stem vowel in the Präteritum. The ich and er/sie/es forms are identical: ich schrieb, er schrieb."},

{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: sein (war)",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"war",src:"I was"},{pronoun:"du",form:"warst",src:"you were"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"war",src:"he/she/it was"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"waren",src:"we were"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"wart",src:"you all were"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"waren",src:"they/you (formal) were"}]}],note:"Only 4 forms: war, warst, wart, waren. ich and er/sie/es share: war. Sein and haben ALWAYS use Präteritum, even in conversation."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: haben (hatte)",groups:[{label:"Singular",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"hatte",src:"I had"},{pronoun:"du",form:"hattest",src:"you had"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"hatte",src:"he/she/it had"}]},{label:"Plural",rows:[{pronoun:"wir",form:"hatten",src:"we had"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"hattet",src:"you all had"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"hatten",src:"they/you (formal) had"}]}],note:"Only 4 forms: hatte, hattest, hattet, hatten. ich and er/sie/es share: hatte."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: Schwache Verben (machen)",groups:[{label:"Konjugation",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"machte",src:"I did/made"},{pronoun:"du",form:"machtest",src:"you did/made"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"machte",src:"he/she/it did/made"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"machten",src:"we did/made"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"machtet",src:"you all did/made"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"machten",src:"they/you did/made"}]}],note:"ich = er/sie/es (both -te). wir = sie/Sie (both -ten). Same pattern for ALL weak verbs.",deepDive:{title:"The -ete Exception",text:"Verbs with stems ending in -t/-d add an extra -e:\narbeiten: arbeitete (not arbeitte)\nwarten: wartete\nreden: redete\n\nWhy? Arbeitte is impossible to pronounce. The extra -e is a pronunciation aid."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: gehen und kommen",groups:[{label:"gehen (ging)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"ging",src:"I went"},{pronoun:"du",form:"gingst",src:"you went"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"ging",src:"he/she/it went"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"gingen",src:"we went"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"gingt",src:"you all went"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"gingen",src:"they/you went"}]},{label:"kommen (kam)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"kam",src:"I came"},{pronoun:"du",form:"kamst",src:"you came"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"kam",src:"he/she/it came"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"kamen",src:"we came"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"kamt",src:"you all came"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"kamen",src:"they/you came"}]}],note:"ich = er/sie/es (no ending). du adds -st. ihr adds -t. wir/sie/Sie add -en."},
{type:"tip",title:"Vowel Change Groups: Strong Verbs",text:"Strong verbs follow patterns:\ne to a (largest group): nahm, sprach, las, gab, kam, sah, fand\nei to ie: schrieb (schreiben), blieb (bleiben), stieg (steigen)\na to u: trug (tragen), fuhr (fahren), wuchs (wachsen)\ne to i: ging (gehen)\n\nThe e-to-a group is by far the largest.\nOnce you know the vowel change, you can predict new forms.",deepDive:{title:"The war/hatte Exception",text:"Most Präteritum forms sound stiff in conversation.\nBut war and hatte are EXCEPTIONS:\n\n'Ich war müde' sounds natural.\n'Ich bin müde gewesen' sounds clunky.\n\nRule: Use war/hatte ALWAYS, in speech AND writing.\nSame applies to modal verbs: konnte, musste, wollte, sollte, durfte."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Präteritum: Gemischte Verben",groups:[{label:"bringen (brachte)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"brachte",src:"I brought"},{pronoun:"du",form:"brachtest",src:"you brought"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"brachte",src:"he/she/it brought"}]},{label:"denken (dachte)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"dachte",src:"I thought"},{pronoun:"du",form:"dachtest",src:"you thought"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"dachte",src:"he/she/it thought"}]},{label:"wissen (wusste)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"wusste",src:"I knew"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wusstest",src:"you knew"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wusste",src:"he/she/it knew"}]}],note:"Mixed verbs: vowel change AND -te ending. Three types:\n1. Weak (regular): stem + -te (machte)\n2. Strong (irregular): vowel change, no -te (ging)\n3. Mixed: vowel change + -te (brachte, dachte, wusste)"},
{type:"teach",trg:"wissen",src:"to know (a fact)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: weiß/wusste/gewusst.\n'Ich weiß es nicht' = I don't know.",example:"A: Weißt du, wo das Büro ist?\nB: Ja, ich weiß es. Zweiter Stock.\nA: Wusste Verumius das?\nB: Nein, er wusste es nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know where the office is?\nB: Yes, I know. Second floor.\nA: Did Verumius know that?\nB: No, he didn't know.",funFact:"Wissen vs. kennen: wissen = to know a FACT, kennen = to know a PERSON or PLACE. 'Ich weiß die Antwort' but 'Ich kenne diesen Mann.' This is one of the most common mistakes for German learners.",deepDive:{title:"wissen vs. kennen",text:"wissen = knowing FACTS:\nIch weiß, wo er wohnt. (I know where he lives.)\nIch weiß die Antwort. (I know the answer.)\nIch wusste das nicht. (I did not know that.)\n\nkennen = being familiar with a person, place, or thing:\nIch kenne diesen Mann. (I know this man.)\nKennst du Berlin? (Do you know Berlin?)\nIch kannte das Lied nicht. (I did not know the song.)\n\nkennen always takes a DIRECT OBJECT.\nwissen can take dass-clauses."}},
{type:"teach",trg:"kennen",src:"to know (a person/place)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Mixed verb: kennen/kannte/gekannt.\n'Ich kenne ihn' = I know him (personally).",example:"A: Kennen Sie Herrn Müller?\nB: Ja, ich kenne ihn seit Jahren.\nA: Und kennen Sie Hamburg?\nB: Nein, ich kannte nur Berlin, bis ich hierherkam.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know Mr. Müller?\nB: Yes, I have known him for years.\nA: And do you know Hamburg?\nB: No, I only knew Berlin until I came here.",funFact:"Kennen is a mixed verb: the stem vowel changes (kennen/kannte) AND it takes the -te ending. Part of the kennen/kannte/gekannt family with nennen/nannte and rennen/rannte."},

{type:"mc",q:"Yilmaz schreibt auf Verumius' Lebenslauf: 'Er studierte drei Jahre in Istanbul.' Welche Zeitform ist 'studierte'?",opts:["Futur I","das Perfekt","das Präsens","Präteritum"],ans:"Präteritum",hint:"The -te ending on a regular verb signals the formal written past tense."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er {1} nach Deutschland und fand eine neue Heimat.",a:["kam"],opts:["kam","kommt","gekommen","kommen"],hint:"Kommen in the Präteritum changes its vowel completely. Think of English 'came.'",sSrc:"He came to Germany and found a new home."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius sagt: 'Ich kenne Berlin.' Warum benutzt er 'kennen' und nicht 'wissen'?",opts:["Kennen ist ausschließlich für Fakten","Kennen ist für Personen und Orte","Kennen ist immer formeller","Es gibt gar keinen Unterschied"],ans:"Kennen ist für Personen und Orte",hint:"One verb is for facts and clauses, the other is for familiarity with people and places."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Bitte {1} Sie Ihre Telefonnummer {2}.",blanks:{"1":"geben","2":"an"},pool:["geben","an","angeben","sagen","aus","mit"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to state or specify. The prefix goes to the end.",sSrc:"Please state your phone number."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"amused",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Und vergiss nicht: ein professionelles Foto. Kein Selfie, kein Urlaub, kein Katzenpullover. Willkommen in Deutschland.",src:"And do not forget: a professional photo. No selfie, no vacation, no cat sweater. Welcome to Germany."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 5: Ich würde mich freuen ====================
{id:"deu_r13l5",title:"Ich würde mich freuen",icon:"🤝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ich würde mich freuen",desc:"Master the Konjunktiv II with würde + infinitive. Express polite wishes and requests. Write formal application sentences.",goals:["Master Konjunktiv II with würde + infinitive","Express polite wishes and requests","Write formal application sentences"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Aushilfe",src:"the temporary worker",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Aus (out) + Hilfe (help).\nA casual or temporary worker.",example:"A: Wir suchen eine Aushilfe für den Sommer.\nB: Für wie viele Stunden?\nA: Zwanzig Stunden pro Woche.\nB: Das passt. Ich bewerbe mich.",exampleSrc:"A: We are looking for temporary help for the summer.\nB: For how many hours?\nA: Twenty hours per week.\nB: That fits. I will apply.",funFact:"Many students work as Aushilfe alongside their studies. 'Aushilfsjob' is a part-time or temporary job. Die Aushilfe is feminine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Teilzeit",src:"part-time",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Teil (part) + Zeit (time).\n'Teilzeitarbeit' = part-time work.",example:"A: Arbeiten Sie Vollzeit oder Teilzeit?\nB: Teilzeit. Dreißig Stunden.\nA: Warum Teilzeit?\nB: Ich studiere noch nebenbei.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you work full-time or part-time?\nB: Part-time. Thirty hours.\nA: Why part-time?\nB: I am still studying on the side.",funFact:"In Germany, parents have a legal right to switch to Teilzeit after having children. Teil (part) + Zeit (time)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vollzeit",src:"full-time",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Voll (full) + Zeit (time).\nTypically 38-40 hours per week in Germany.",example:"A: Suchen Sie eine Vollzeitstelle?\nB: Ja, vierzig Stunden pro Woche.\nA: Wir bieten flexible Vollzeit.\nB: Das klingt gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you looking for a full-time position?\nB: Yes, forty hours per week.\nA: We offer flexible full-time.\nB: That sounds good.",funFact:"Typically 38 to 40 hours per week in Germany. 'Vollzeitstelle' (full-time position). The contrast pair: Teilzeit vs. Vollzeit appears in every job listing."},
{type:"fb",s:"Arbeiten Sie {1} oder Teilzeit?",a:["Vollzeit"],opts:["Vollzeit","Halbtags","Aushilfe","Arbeit"],hint:"The opposite of part-time. Full + time. Typically 38-40 hours per week in Germany.",sSrc:"Do you work full-time or part-time?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Einkommen",src:"the income",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Ein (in) + kommen (to come).\nIncome, literally what 'comes in.'",example:"A: Wie hoch ist Ihr Einkommen?\nB: Das möchte ich nicht sagen.\nA: Verstehe. In Deutschland spricht man nicht gern darüber.\nB: Genau. Das ist privat.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is your income?\nB: I would rather not say.\nA: I understand. In Germany people don't like to talk about it.\nB: Exactly. That is private.",funFact:"Germans rarely discuss their Einkommen openly. Talking about salary is considered impolite in many social situations. What 'comes in' stays private."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Angestellte",src:"the employee (white-collar)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun (changes with article: der/die Angestellte).\nFrom 'anstellen' (to employ). Declines like an adjective.",example:"A: Wie viele Angestellte hat die Firma?\nB: Etwa zweihundert Angestellte.\nA: Und Arbeiter?\nB: Noch einmal dreihundert.",exampleSrc:"A: How many employees does the company have?\nB: About two hundred employees.\nA: And workers?\nB: Another three hundred.",funFact:"Der/die Angestellte changes gender with the article. Like 'Deutsche,' it declines as an adjective. The distinction between Arbeiter and Angestellte was legally important until 2005."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Arbeiter",src:"the worker (blue-collar)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Arbeit (work) + -er (person).\nTraditionally blue-collar.",example:"A: Die Arbeiter in der Fabrik streiken.\nB: Warum?\nA: Sie wollen bessere Arbeitsbedingungen.\nB: Das ist ihr Recht.",exampleSrc:"A: The workers in the factory are striking.\nB: Why?\nA: They want better working conditions.\nB: That is their right.",funFact:"The distinction between Arbeiter and Angestellte was legally important in Germany until 2005 for insurance purposes. Traditionally, Arbeiter did manual labor."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Arbeiterin",src:"the worker (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Arbeiter + '-in.'\nSame pattern: masculine + -in = feminine.",example:"A: Die Arbeiterin hat zehn Jahre Erfahrung.\nB: In welchem Bereich?\nA: In der Produktion.\nB: Das ist beeindruckend.",exampleSrc:"A: The worker has ten years of experience.\nB: In which field?\nA: In production.\nB: That is impressive.",funFact:"Same pattern as always: masculine profession + -in = feminine. The German language never leaves you without a feminine form."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Angestellte und Arbeiter?",opts:["Es gibt heutzutage kaum einen realen Unterschied","Arbeiter verdienen in der Regel deutlich viel mehr","Angestellte sind per Definition ausschlie\u00dflich weiblich","Angestellte arbeiten in B\u00fcros, Arbeiter arbeiten manuell"],ans:"Angestellte arbeiten in B\u00fcros, Arbeiter arbeiten manuell",hint:"One traditionally referred to white-collar office workers, the other to blue-collar manual laborers."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Arbeitsstelle",src:"the job, the position",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Arbeit + Stelle (position).\nMore formal than 'Job.'",example:"A: Ich suche eine neue Arbeitsstelle.\nB: In welchem Bereich?\nA: Im Marketing.\nB: Ich kenne eine offene Arbeitsstelle bei Bosch.",exampleSrc:"A: I am looking for a new job.\nB: In which field?\nA: In marketing.\nB: I know an open position at Bosch.",funFact:"'Ich suche eine Arbeitsstelle' (I am looking for a job). More formal than 'Job.' Die Arbeitsstelle is feminine because Stelle is feminine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Arbeitserlaubnis",src:"the work permit",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Arbeit + Erlaubnis (permission).\nEssential for non-EU citizens.",example:"A: Haben Sie eine Arbeitserlaubnis?\nB: Ja, seit letztem Jahr.\nA: Gut. Ohne Arbeitserlaubnis geht es nicht.\nB: Ich weiß. Es war ein langer Prozess.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a work permit?\nB: Yes, since last year.\nA: Good. Without a work permit it is not possible.\nB: I know. It was a long process.",funFact:"Die Arbeitserlaubnis is essential for non-EU citizens in Germany. Without it, you cannot legally work. The feminine gender comes from Erlaubnis."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Arbeitslosigkeit",src:"the unemployment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Arbeitslos (jobless) + -igkeit.\nThe -keit/-igkeit suffix always creates feminine nouns.",example:"A: Die Arbeitslosigkeit sinkt.\nB: Das sind gute Nachrichten.\nA: Ja, es gibt mehr Arbeitsstellen.\nB: Besonders im IT-Bereich.",exampleSrc:"A: Unemployment is falling.\nB: That is good news.\nA: Yes, there are more jobs.\nB: Especially in the IT field.",funFact:"The German social safety net includes 'Arbeitslosengeld' (unemployment benefits). The -keit/-igkeit suffix always creates feminine nouns."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Die Arbeitslosigkeit sinkt.' Was bedeutet Arbeitslosigkeit?",opts:["work permit","working conditions","unemployment","employment"],ans:"unemployment",hint:"Arbeitslos means jobless. The -igkeit suffix turns the adjective into a feminine noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lehrerin",src:"the teacher (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Lehrer (teacher) + '-in.'\nTeaching is highly respected in Germany.",example:"A: Meine Lehrerin ist sehr streng.\nB: Streng aber fair?\nA: Ja, genau. Ich lerne viel.\nB: Das ist eine gute Lehrerin.",exampleSrc:"A: My teacher is very strict.\nB: Strict but fair?\nA: Yes, exactly. I learn a lot.\nB: That is a good teacher.",funFact:"Teaching is one of the most respected professions in Germany. Lehrer/Lehrerin are civil servants (Beamte) in most German states, with excellent benefits."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Meister",src:"the master craftsman",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From Latin 'magister.'\nA protected title requiring years of training.",example:"A: Sind Sie Meister?\nB: Ja, Meister im Elektrohandwerk.\nA: Wie lange hat das gedauert?\nB: Drei Jahre Ausbildung plus Meisterprüfung.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a master craftsman?\nB: Yes, master in electrical trade.\nA: How long did that take?\nB: Three years of training plus the master exam.",funFact:"Der Meister title requires years of training plus a demanding exam. 'Meister' is a protected title in Germany. You cannot call yourself one without the certificate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Profi",src:"the pro, the professional",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Short for 'Professional.'\nBorrowed from English. Informal but common.",example:"A: Er ist ein echter Profi.\nB: Ja, er arbeitet sehr genau.\nA: Profis machen keine Fehler.\nB: Na ja, weniger Fehler als andere.",exampleSrc:"A: He is a real pro.\nB: Yes, he works very precisely.\nA: Pros don't make mistakes.\nB: Well, fewer mistakes than others.",funFact:"Short for 'Professional.' Borrowed from English. 'Er ist ein echter Profi' (He is a real pro). Colloquial but understood everywhere."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der {1} ist ein geschützter Titel in Deutschland.",a:["Meister"],opts:["Meister","Profi","Arbeiter","Angestellte"],hint:"The master craftsman title requires years of training plus a demanding exam.",sSrc:"The master craftsman is a protected title in Germany."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l5b",title:"Ich würde mich freuen (Teil 2)",icon:"🤝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ich würde mich freuen (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fachmann",src:"the expert, the specialist (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Fach (field) + Mann (man).\n'Fragen Sie einen Fachmann.'",example:"A: Wir brauchen einen Fachmann.\nB: Für welchen Bereich?\nA: Für IT-Sicherheit.\nB: Ich kenne einen guten Fachmann.",exampleSrc:"A: We need an expert.\nB: For which field?\nA: For IT security.\nB: I know a good expert.",funFact:"'Fragen Sie einen Fachmann' (Ask an expert) is common advice in Germany. Der Fachmann is the go-to person when you need specialized knowledge."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fachfrau",src:"the expert, the specialist (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Fach + Frau.\nThe modern feminine form of Fachmann.",example:"A: Die Fachfrau hat das Problem gelöst.\nB: In nur einer Stunde?\nA: Ja, sie ist wirklich kompetent.\nB: Wir sollten sie öfter fragen.",exampleSrc:"A: The expert solved the problem.\nB: In only one hour?\nA: Yes, she is really competent.\nB: We should ask her more often.",funFact:"The modern feminine form. Some companies now use 'Fachkraft' (skilled worker) as a gender-neutral alternative instead of Fachmann/Fachfrau."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fachleute",src:"the experts (plural)",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Plural of Fachmann/Fachfrau.\nOne of the few words where the plural changes entirely.",example:"A: Wir brauchen Fachleute für das Projekt.\nB: Wie viele?\nA: Mindestens drei Fachleute.\nB: Ich suche sofort.",exampleSrc:"A: We need experts for the project.\nB: How many?\nA: At least three experts.\nB: I will search immediately.",funFact:"Not 'Fachmänner' or 'Fachfrauen' but 'Fachleute' (professional people). One of the few German words where the plural changes the second element entirely."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} (plural) sind die Experten auf diesem Gebiet.",a:["Fachleute"],opts:["Fachleute","Fachmann","Fachfrau","Fachmänner"],hint:"The inclusive plural form for subject-matter experts, used when referring to a mixed or unspecified group.",sSrc:"The experts are the specialists in this field."},
{type:"teach",trg:"absolut",src:"absolute, absolutely",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'absolutus' (completed/perfect).\nStress on the last syllable: ab-so-LOOT.",example:"A: Sind Sie sicher?\nB: Absolut. Hundert Prozent.\nA: Das ist absolut richtig.\nB: Danke für die Bestätigung.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you sure?\nB: Absolutely. One hundred percent.\nA: That is absolutely right.\nB: Thank you for the confirmation.",funFact:"Same word in English, French, and German. 'Absolut richtig!' (Absolutely right!). Stress on the last syllable: ab-so-LOOT."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wie heißt der Plural von Fachmann und Fachfrau?",opts:["Fachmänner","Fachfrauen","Fachleute","Fachpersonen"],ans:"Fachleute",hint:"One of the few German words where the plural changes the second element entirely."},
{type:"teach",trg:"flexibel",src:"flexible",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'flexibilis.'\n'Flexible Arbeitszeiten' = flexible working hours.",example:"A: Sind Sie zeitlich flexibel?\nB: Ja, sehr flexibel.\nA: Auch am Wochenende?\nB: Wenn nötig, ja.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you flexible with your time?\nB: Yes, very flexible.\nA: Also on weekends?\nB: If necessary, yes.",funFact:"'Flexible Arbeitszeiten' (flexible working hours) is the most desired benefit in German job surveys. Stress on the second syllable: flek-SEE-bel."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ideal",src:"ideal, perfect",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'idea.'\n'Der ideale Kandidat' = the ideal candidate.",example:"A: Das ist die ideale Stelle für Sie.\nB: Warum?\nA: Sie passt perfekt zu Ihren Qualifikationen.\nB: Das klingt ideal!",exampleSrc:"A: This is the ideal position for you.\nB: Why?\nA: It fits your qualifications perfectly.\nB: That sounds ideal!",funFact:"'Der ideale Kandidat' (the ideal candidate) is what every job listing describes. Same word internationally. Stress on the last syllable: ee-de-AHL."},
{type:"teach",trg:"individuell",src:"individual, personal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'individualis.'\n'Individuelle Lösungen' = individual solutions.",example:"A: Jede Bewerbung muss individuell sein.\nB: Nicht einfach kopieren?\nA: Nein! Individuell anpassen.\nB: Okay, ich schreibe jede einzeln.",exampleSrc:"A: Every application must be individual.\nB: Not just copy?\nA: No! Adapt individually.\nB: Okay, I will write each one separately.",funFact:"'Individuelle Lösungen' (individual solutions) is a phrase from every consulting brochure. Stress on the last syllable: in-di-vi-du-ELL."},
{type:"tip",title:"Konjunktiv II: The Polite Mode",text:"German has a special verb form for wishes, polite requests, and hypotheticals.\n\nThe simplest version: würde + infinitive\n\n'Ich würde mich freuen' (I would be pleased)\n'Würden Sie mir bitte helfen?' (Would you please help me?)\n\nIn applications:\n'Ich würde gern in Ihrem Unternehmen arbeiten.'\n\nThis is softer and more polite than the indicative.\n\nWish sentences:\n'Wenn ich doch nur mehr Erfahrung hätte!'\n(If only I had more experience!)",deepDive:{title:"Würde vs. True Konjunktiv II Forms",text:"Würde + infinitive is the modern, simple form.\n\nBut some verbs have their own Konjunktiv II forms:\nsein: wäre (would be)\nhaben: hätte (would have)\nwerden: würde (would become)\n\nThese 'true' forms sound more elegant.\n'Ich wäre froh' instead of 'Ich würde froh sein'\n'Ich hätte gern' instead of 'Ich würde gern haben'\n\nFor most other verbs, Germans use würde + infinitive."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Konjunktiv II: würde + Infinitiv",groups:[{label:"Konjugation",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"würde ... arbeiten",src:"I would work"},{pronoun:"du",form:"würdest ... arbeiten",src:"you would work"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"würde ... arbeiten",src:"he/she/it would work"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"würden ... arbeiten",src:"we would work"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"würdet ... arbeiten",src:"you all would work"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"würden ... arbeiten",src:"they/you would work"}]},{label:"Wichtige eigene Formen",rows:[{pronoun:"sein",form:"wäre",src:"would be"},{pronoun:"haben",form:"hätte",src:"would have"},{pronoun:"werden",form:"würde",src:"would become"}]}],note:"Würde + infinitive is the standard form for polite requests and wishes in German. Sein and haben use their own forms: wäre, hätte."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} mich sehr {2}, von Ihnen zu hören.",blanks:{"1":"würde","2":"freuen"},pool:["würde","freuen","wurde","gefreut","habe","arbeiten"],hint:"A polite closing line in a cover letter. 'Would' + 'be pleased.'",sSrc:"I would be very pleased to hear from you."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Vollzeit",src:"full-time"},{trg:"Teilzeit",src:"part-time"},{trg:"Aushilfe",src:"temporary worker"},{trg:"Praktikant",src:"intern"},{trg:"Angestellte",src:"employee"},{trg:"Meister",src:"master craftsman"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"thoughtful",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Dein Anschreiben klingt jetzt professionell. 'Ich würde mich freuen.' Perfekt. Aber morgen üben wir das Gespräch. Das wird der schwierige Teil.",src:"Your cover letter sounds professional now. 'I would be pleased.' Perfect. But tomorrow we practice the interview. That will be the difficult part."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'absolut'?",opts:["individual, personal","the employee (white-collar)","full-time","absolute, absolutely"],ans:"absolute, absolutely",hint:"A Latin cognate, same spelling and meaning as in English and French."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sind Sie zeitlich {1}?",a:["flexibel"],opts:["die Lehrerin","flexibel","der Fachmann","die Arbeitslosigkeit"],hint:"An adjective meaning adaptable or bendable. Latin cognate, same in English.",sSrc:"Are you flexible with your time?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'ideal'?",opts:["the experts (plural)","part-time","the temporary worker","ideal, perfect"],ans:"ideal, perfect",hint:"Greek/Latin origin. Identical spelling in English, French, and German."},
{type:"fb",s:"Jede Bewerbung muss {1} sein.",a:["individuell"],opts:["individuell","das Einkommen","flexibel","die Fachfrau"],hint:"An adjective meaning tailored to one person. Latin cognate with -ell ending.",sSrc:"Every application must be individual."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 6: Experten und Kandidaten ====================
{id:"deu_r13l6",title:"Experten und Kandidaten",icon:"👔",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Experten und Kandidaten",desc:"Learn professional job titles and roles. Master masculine and feminine forms. Build your networking vocabulary.",goals:["Learn professional job titles and roles","Master masculine and feminine forms","Build your networking vocabulary"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"tense",art:"de-vhs-classroom-interview",trg:"Der VHS-Klassenraum wurde umgebaut. Zwei Stühle stehen sich gegenüber. Yilmaz sitzt mit perfekter Haltung, Klemmbrett in der Hand. Verumius zupft an seinem Kragen.",src:"The VHS classroom has been rearranged. Two chairs face each other. Yilmaz sits with perfect posture, clipboard in hand. Verumius tugs at his collar."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"professional",trg:"Guten Tag, Herr Verumius. Nehmen Sie bitte Platz. Könnten Sie sich kurz vorstellen?",src:"Good day, Mr. Verumius. Please take a seat. Could you briefly introduce yourself?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",trg:"Guten Tag. Ich... ähm... Ich studierte Linguistik in Istanbul und arbeitete als Übersetzer. Ich würde gern in Ihrem Unternehmen arbeiten.",src:"Good day. I... um... I studied linguistics in Istanbul and worked as a translator. I would like to work in your company."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"evaluating",trg:"Gut. Sie sollten auch Ihre Stärken nennen. Was könnten Sie unserem Team bieten?",src:"Good. You should also mention your strengths. What could you offer our team?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"concentrating",trg:"Ich spreche fließend drei Sprachen. Ich könnte Ihre internationale Kommunikation verbessern.",src:"I speak three languages fluently. I could improve your international communication."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"pleased",trg:"Gut. Du bist bereit.",src:"Good. You are ready."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Experte",src:"the expert",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From French 'expert.'\nN-Deklination: Experte, Experten, Experten.",example:"A: Wir brauchen einen Experten.\nB: Für welches Thema?\nA: Für Datenschutz.\nB: Ich kenne einen Experten in Berlin.",exampleSrc:"A: We need an expert.\nB: For which topic?\nA: For data protection.\nB: I know an expert in Berlin.",funFact:"Der Experte belongs to the 'n-Deklination': Experte, Experten, Experten. The -e ending on a masculine noun is a clue for this special declension."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Spezialist",src:"the specialist",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From Latin 'specialis.'\nThe -ist ending always makes masculine nouns.",example:"A: Sie ist Spezialistin für Marketing.\nB: Und er ist Spezialist für Finanzen.\nA: Zusammen sind sie ein gutes Team.\nB: Genau. Jeder hat seine Stärke.",exampleSrc:"A: She is a specialist in marketing.\nB: And he is a specialist in finance.\nA: Together they are a good team.\nB: Exactly. Everyone has their strength.",funFact:"The -ist ending comes from Latin/French and always makes masculine nouns: Journalist, Tourist, Spezialist. Same pattern across European languages."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Spezialistin",src:"the specialist (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Spezialist + '-in.'\nThe pattern: -ist (masculine) + -in = -istin.",example:"A: Die Spezialistin hat das Problem gelöst.\nB: Welche Spezialistin?\nA: Frau Dr. Müller. IT-Sicherheit.\nB: Ah ja. Sie ist wirklich gut.",exampleSrc:"A: The specialist solved the problem.\nB: Which specialist?\nA: Dr. Müller. IT security.\nB: Ah yes. She is really good.",funFact:"The pattern holds: -ist (masculine) + -in = -istin (feminine). Spezialist becomes Spezialistin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Unternehmer",src:"the entrepreneur",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Unter (under) + nehmen (to take).\nSomeone who 'undertakes' business.",example:"A: Er ist ein erfolgreicher Unternehmer.\nB: Was für ein Unternehmen hat er?\nA: Eine Softwarefirma.\nB: Seit wann ist er Unternehmer?",exampleSrc:"A: He is a successful entrepreneur.\nB: What kind of company does he have?\nA: A software company.\nB: Since when has he been an entrepreneur?",funFact:"Germany has 3.5 million Unternehmer. The Mittelstand (medium-sized businesses) are the backbone of the economy. Literally 'someone who undertakes.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir brauchen einen {1} für Datenschutz.",a:["Experten"],opts:["Experten","Spezialist","Unternehmer","Kandidat"],hint:"This noun follows n-Deklination. It changes its ending in accusative, dative, and genitive cases.",sSrc:"We need an expert for data protection."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Unternehmerin",src:"the entrepreneur (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Unternehmer + '-in.'\n'Gründerinnen' is a buzzword in the startup scene.",example:"A: Die Unternehmerin hat drei Firmen gegründet.\nB: Beeindruckend. In welchen Bereichen?\nA: Technologie und Bildung.\nB: Eine echte Vorreiterin.",exampleSrc:"A: The entrepreneur has founded three companies.\nB: Impressive. In which fields?\nA: Technology and education.\nB: A true pioneer.",funFact:"Female entrepreneurs are growing fast in Germany. 'Gründerinnen' (female founders) is a buzzword in the German startup scene."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kandidat",src:"the candidate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From Latin 'candidatus' (clothed in white).\nN-Deklination: Kandidat, Kandidaten.",example:"A: Wie viele Kandidaten gibt es?\nB: Fünfzig Kandidaten für drei Stellen.\nA: Das ist viel Konkurrenz.\nB: Ja, aber unser Kandidat ist stark.",exampleSrc:"A: How many candidates are there?\nB: Fifty candidates for three positions.\nA: That is a lot of competition.\nB: Yes, but our candidate is strong.",funFact:"White togas were worn by Romans seeking office. Der Kandidat also belongs to the n-Deklination: Kandidat, Kandidaten. From Latin 'candidatus.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Mitglied",src:"the member",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Mit (with) + Glied (limb/member).\nThere are 600,000 registered Vereine in Germany.",example:"A: Sind Sie Mitglied in einem Verein?\nB: Ja, im Sportverein.\nA: Wie viele Mitglieder hat der Verein?\nB: Etwa dreihundert.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a member of a club?\nB: Yes, in a sports club.\nA: How many members does the club have?\nB: About three hundred.",funFact:"Germans love club membership: 'Vereinsmitglied' (club member). There are 600,000 registered Vereine in Germany. Das Mitglied is neuter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Visitenkarte",src:"the business card",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Visite (visit) + Karte (card).\nStill standard practice at networking events.",example:"A: Haben Sie eine Visitenkarte?\nB: Ja, hier bitte.\nA: Danke. Ich melde mich bei Ihnen.\nB: Gern. Meine E-Mail steht auf der Karte.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a business card?\nB: Yes, here you go.\nA: Thank you. I will get in touch.\nB: Gladly. My email is on the card.",funFact:"In German business culture, exchanging Visitenkarten is still standard practice at meetings and networking events. Digital alternatives are growing but paper persists."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Experte",src:"expert"},{trg:"Spezialistin",src:"specialist (female)"},{trg:"Unternehmer",src:"entrepreneur"},{trg:"Kandidat",src:"candidate"},{trg:"Mitglied",src:"member"},{trg:"Visitenkarte",src:"business card"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort beschreibt eine weibliche Unternehmerin?",opts:["die Unternehmung","der Unternehmer","das Unternehmen","die Unternehmerin"],ans:"die Unternehmerin",hint:"The feminine form adds -in to the masculine noun. Same pattern as Spezialist/Spezialistin."},
{type:"fb",s:"Haben Sie eine {1}? Hier ist meine E-Mail-Adresse.",a:["Visitenkarte"],opts:["Visitenkarte","Mitglied","Kandidat","Wirtschaft"],hint:"A small card exchanged at networking events. Still standard practice in Germany.",sSrc:"Do you have a business card? Here is my email address."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 7: Könnten Sie das wiederholen? ====================
{id:"deu_r13l7",title:"Könnten Sie das wiederholen?",icon:"🎤",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Könnten Sie das wiederholen?",desc:"Learn interview adjectives and action verbs. Master Konjunktiv II of modal verbs. Practice polite professional German.",goals:["Learn interview adjectives and action verbs","Master Konjunktiv II of modal verbs","Practice polite professional German"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wirtschaft",src:"the economy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'Wirt' (host/innkeeper).\n'Wirtschaftswunder' = the economic miracle.",example:"A: Wie steht die deutsche Wirtschaft?\nB: Gut. Die Wirtschaft wächst.\nA: In welchem Bereich?\nB: Besonders in der Technologie.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the German economy?\nB: Good. The economy is growing.\nA: In which sector?\nB: Especially in technology.",funFact:"Originally meant 'hosting/hospitality' and expanded to mean all economic activity. 'Wirtschaftswunder' (economic miracle) describes Germany's post-war recovery."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verantwortung",src:"the responsibility",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ver- + Antwortung (answering).\nLiterally 'answering for' something.",example:"A: Diese Stelle hat viel Verantwortung.\nB: Das ist mir bewusst.\nA: Sind Sie bereit für die Verantwortung?\nB: Ja, absolut.",exampleSrc:"A: This position has a lot of responsibility.\nB: I am aware of that.\nA: Are you ready for the responsibility?\nB: Yes, absolutely.",funFact:"'Verantwortung übernehmen' (to take responsibility) is a phrase German managers use constantly. Responsibility is literally 'answering for' something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Voraussetzung",src:"the prerequisite, the requirement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Voraus (ahead) + Setzung (setting).\nSomething set ahead of you.",example:"A: Was sind die Voraussetzungen für die Stelle?\nB: Ein Abschluss und drei Jahre Erfahrung.\nA: Erfülle ich die Voraussetzungen?\nB: Ja, alle.",exampleSrc:"A: What are the requirements for the position?\nB: A degree and three years of experience.\nA: Do I meet the requirements?\nB: Yes, all of them.",funFact:"'Voraussetzungen für die Stelle' (requirements for the position) is standard in job ads. Always feminine because of the -ung ending."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Diese Stelle hat viel Verantwortung.' Was bedeutet Verantwortung?",opts:["responsibility","careful preparation","formal requirement","growing economy"],ans:"responsibility",hint:"Literally 'answering for' something. Ver- + Antwortung. A key word in professional German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausgezeichnet",src:"excellent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Past participle of 'auszeichnen' (to distinguish).\nLiterally 'marked out' as special.",example:"A: Wie sind Ihre Deutschkenntnisse?\nB: Ausgezeichnet. Ich habe ein C1-Zertifikat.\nA: Ausgezeichnet! Das freut uns.\nB: Danke.",exampleSrc:"A: How is your German?\nB: Excellent. I have a C1 certificate.\nA: Excellent! We are pleased.\nB: Thank you.",funFact:"'Ausgezeichnete Deutschkenntnisse' (excellent German skills) is the highest level on job listings. Past participle used as adjective: 'marked out' as special."},
{type:"teach",trg:"geeignet",src:"suitable, qualified",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Past participle of 'eignen' (to be suitable).\n'Für diese Stelle geeignet.'",example:"A: Ist er für die Stelle geeignet?\nB: Ja, er ist sehr gut geeignet.\nA: Warum?\nB: Er hat alle erforderlichen Qualifikationen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is he suitable for the position?\nB: Yes, he is very well suited.\nA: Why?\nB: He has all the required qualifications.",funFact:"The ge- prefix marks it as a past participle turned adjective. 'Für diese Stelle geeignet' (suitable for this position)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"fließend",src:"fluent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Present participle of 'fließen' (to flow).\nLanguage that flows without stopping.",example:"A: Sprechen Sie fließend Deutsch?\nB: Ja, fließend. Und auch Englisch.\nA: Und Türkisch?\nB: Das ist meine Muttersprache.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you speak fluent German?\nB: Yes, fluently. And also English.\nA: And Turkish?\nB: That is my mother tongue.",funFact:"'Fließend Deutsch sprechen' (to speak fluent German) means your German flows without stopping. Language proficiency that moves like water."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eindeutig",src:"unambiguous, clear",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ein (one) + deutig (meaning/interpretation).\nHaving only one possible meaning.",example:"A: Das Ergebnis ist eindeutig.\nB: Ja, da gibt es keinen Zweifel.\nA: Eindeutig der beste Kandidat.\nB: Einverstanden.",exampleSrc:"A: The result is clear.\nB: Yes, there is no doubt.\nA: Clearly the best candidate.\nB: Agreed.",funFact:"Having only one possible meaning. 'Das Ergebnis ist eindeutig' (The result is clear). The opposite: 'mehrdeutig' (ambiguous, having multiple meanings)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eignen",src:"to be suitable",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive: 'sich eignen für.'\nRelated to 'eigen' (own).",example:"A: Eignen Sie sich für Teamarbeit?\nB: Ja, ich eigne mich gut für Teams.\nA: Und für Einzelarbeit?\nB: Auch. Ich bin flexibel.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you suited for teamwork?\nB: Yes, I am well suited for teams.\nA: And for working alone?\nB: Also. I am flexible.",funFact:"'Sich eignen für' (to be suited for). Reflexive in this meaning. Related to 'eigen' (own). What is 'eigenartig' (peculiar) is uniquely its own."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sprechen Sie {1} Deutsch?",a:["fließend"],opts:["fließend","eindeutig","geeignet","ausgezeichnet"],hint:"The highest level of spoken language ability: smooth, continuous, with no hesitation or searching for words.",sSrc:"Do you speak fluent German?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"einstellen",src:"to hire, to employ",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ein + stellen (to place).\n'Wir stellen Sie ein' = We are hiring you.",example:"A: Wann stellen Sie neue Mitarbeiter ein?\nB: Ab nächstem Monat.\nA: Wie viele stellen Sie ein?\nB: Drei neue Mitarbeiter.",exampleSrc:"A: When do you hire new employees?\nB: Starting next month.\nA: How many will you hire?\nB: Three new employees.",funFact:"Separable verb: 'Wir stellen Sie ein' (We are hiring you). Also means 'to adjust' (ein Gerät einstellen) or 'to stop' (die Produktion einstellen). Context decides."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bieten",src:"to offer",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: bieten/bot/geboten.\n'Was können Sie uns bieten?'",example:"A: Was können Sie uns bieten?\nB: Erfahrung, Sprachkenntnisse und Motivation.\nA: Und was bieten wir Ihnen?\nB: Eine interessante Arbeitsstelle.",exampleSrc:"A: What can you offer us?\nB: Experience, language skills, and motivation.\nA: And what do we offer you?\nB: An interesting job.",funFact:"'Was können Sie uns bieten?' (What can you offer us?) is the classic interview question. Strong verb: bieten/bot/geboten. Related to English 'bid.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"bemühen",src:"to make an effort",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive: 'sich bemühen.'\nFormal: 'Ich bemühe mich um eine Stelle.'",example:"A: Ich bemühe mich sehr um diese Stelle.\nB: Das sehe ich. Ihr Lebenslauf ist beeindruckend.\nA: Danke. Ich bemühe mich immer um Qualität.\nB: Das ist eine gute Eigenschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: I am making a great effort for this position.\nB: I can see that. Your CV is impressive.\nA: Thank you. I always strive for quality.\nB: That is a good quality.",funFact:"In formal letters: 'Ich bemühe mich um eine Stelle' (I am applying for a position). Old-fashioned but still used in very formal applications. Be- + mühen (to toil)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beteiligen",src:"to participate, to involve",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive: 'sich beteiligen an.'\nMaking yourself part of something.",example:"A: Möchten Sie sich am Projekt beteiligen?\nB: Ja, gern. Wie kann ich mich beteiligen?\nA: Sie könnten die Übersetzungen übernehmen.\nB: Das mache ich gern.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like to participate in the project?\nB: Yes, gladly. How can I participate?\nA: You could take over the translations.\nB: I would gladly do that.",funFact:"'An einem Projekt beteiligt sein' (to be involved in a project). Reflexive: 'Ich beteilige mich an der Diskussion.' Making yourself part of something."},
{type:"tip",title:"Konjunktiv II of Modal Verbs: The Polite Tools",text:"Modal verbs have their own Konjunktiv II forms. No 'würde' needed.\n\nkönnen: könnte (could)\nmüssen: müsste (would have to)\ndürfen: dürfte (might/may I)\nsollen: sollte (should)\nwollen: wollte (would want)\n\nThese are MORE POLITE than würde:\n'Könnten Sie mir helfen?' is softer than\n'Würden Sie mir helfen?'\n\nUse modal Konjunktiv II forms in job interviews, emails, and with strangers.",deepDive:{title:"Könnten vs. konnten: One Letter, Big Difference",text:"Könnten (Konjunktiv II) = could (polite/hypothetical)\nKonnten (Präteritum) = could (past: were able to)\n\nThe umlaut makes the difference:\n'Sie könnten mir helfen' = You could help me (polite request)\n'Sie konnten mir helfen' = You were able to help me (past fact)\n\nSame rule for all modal verbs:\nmüsste (should) vs. musste (had to)\ndürfte (might) vs. durfte (was allowed to)"}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Konjunktiv II: Modalverben",groups:[{label:"Modale Konjunktiv-II-Formen",rows:[{pronoun:"können",form:"könnte",src:"could"},{pronoun:"müssen",form:"müsste",src:"would have to"},{pronoun:"dürfen",form:"dürfte",src:"might/would be allowed to"},{pronoun:"sollen",form:"sollte",src:"should"},{pronoun:"wollen",form:"wollte",src:"would want"}]},{label:"Konjugation: könnte",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"könnte",src:"I could"},{pronoun:"du",form:"könntest",src:"you could"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"könnte",src:"he/she/it could"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"könnten",src:"we could"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"könntet",src:"you all could"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"könnten",src:"they/you could"}]}],note:"Modal Konjunktiv II forms are more polite than würde + infinitive. ich and er/sie/es have identical forms: ich könnte, er könnte."},
{type:"mc",q:"Yilmaz fragt: 'Könnten Sie sich kurz vorstellen?' Warum benutzt sie 'könnten' statt 'können'?",opts:["Es steht in der Vergangenheit des Satzes","Es ist ein formeller Befehl oder Auftrag","Es ist höflicher und formeller","Es bedeutet hier kontextuell etwas anderes"],ans:"Es ist höflicher und formeller",hint:"The Konjunktiv II of modals softens the request. Could you vs. Can you."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sie {1} auch Ihre Stärken nennen.",a:["sollten"],opts:["sollten","sollen","müssen","wollen"],hint:"Yilmaz gives advice here, not a strict order. The Konjunktiv II of a duty verb creates gentle advice.",sSrc:"You should also mention your strengths."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius sagt: 'Ich studierte in Istanbul und könnte Ihre Kommunikation verbessern.' Welche Zeitformen?",opts:["Beide Sätze im Konjunktiv II","Beide Sätze im Präteritum","Präsens zuerst, dann Konjunktiv II","Präteritum + Konjunktiv II"],ans:"Präteritum + Konjunktiv II",hint:"The first verb describes the past. The second expresses a polite possibility."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} Sie mir bitte {2}, was genau die Stelle beinhaltet?",blanks:{"1":"Könnten","2":"sagen"},pool:["Könnten","sagen","Können","gesagt","Sollten","erklären"],hint:"A polite interview question: 'Could you please tell me...' Modal Konjunktiv II + Infinitiv.",sSrc:"Could you please tell me what exactly the position involves?"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Voraussetzung",src:"prerequisite"},{trg:"Verantwortung",src:"responsibility"},{trg:"Wirtschaft",src:"economy"},{trg:"ausgezeichnet",src:"excellent"},{trg:"geeignet",src:"suitable"},{trg:"fließend",src:"fluent"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir {1} ab nächstem Monat drei neue Mitarbeiter ein.",a:["stellen"],opts:["stellen","arbeiten","einstellen","machen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to hire. The prefix 'ein' is already at the end.",sSrc:"We will hire three new employees starting next month."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"satisfied",art:"de-vhs-classroom-interview",trg:"Verumius. Du hast dich gut geschlagen. Deine Sprache war höflich, deine Antworten klar. Aber vergiss nicht: Augenkontakt. Immer Augenkontakt.",src:"Verumius. You did well. Your language was polite, your answers clear. But do not forget: eye contact. Always eye contact."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} mich gut für Teamarbeit.",a:"eigne",opts:["eigne","eigene","arbeite","melde"],hint:"A reflexive verb meaning to be suited or suitable for something.",sSrc:"I am well suited for teamwork."}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 8: Der perfekte Lebenslauf ====================
{id:"deu_r13l8",title:"Der perfekte Lebenslauf",icon:"✍️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der perfekte Lebenslauf",desc:"Master job search vocabulary. Practice all three grammar constructs in professional context. Write application-level sentences.",goals:["Master job search vocabulary","Practice all three grammar constructs in context","Write application-level sentences"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"coaching",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"So, Verumius. Dein Lebenslauf ist jetzt komplett. Aber du musst auch auf Annoncen reagieren können. Lass uns üben.",src:"So, Verumius. Your CV is now complete. But you also need to be able to respond to job ads. Let us practice."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"determined",trg:"Ich bin bereit. Ich habe die ganze Nacht geübt.",src:"I am ready. I practiced all night."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Annonce",src:"the classified ad",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From French 'annonce' (announcement).\nThe traditional word for a job advertisement.",example:"A: Hast du die Annonce gelesen?\nB: Ja, die klingt interessant.\nA: Bewirb dich schnell.\nB: Ich schreibe heute noch die Bewerbung.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you read the classified ad?\nB: Yes, it sounds interesting.\nA: Apply quickly.\nB: I will write the application today.",funFact:"Die Annonce is the traditional word for a job ad. Modern German also uses 'Stellenanzeige' (position announcement). The French origin gives it elegance."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Inserat",src:"the advertisement",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'inserere' (to insert).\nParticularly in newspapers.",example:"A: Ich habe ein Inserat in der Zeitung gesehen.\nB: Für welche Stelle?\nA: Übersetzer. Genau mein Bereich.\nB: Schick deine Bewerbung sofort ab.",exampleSrc:"A: I saw an ad in the newspaper.\nB: For which position?\nA: Translator. Exactly my field.\nB: Send your application right away.",funFact:"The Swiss and Austrians prefer Inserat. Germans often say Anzeige or Annonce. All three mean the same thing. From Latin 'inserere' (to insert)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nachfrage",src:"the demand, the inquiry",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Nach (after) + Frage (question).\nDemand or a follow-up question.",example:"A: Die Nachfrage nach IT-Experten ist hoch.\nB: Ja, der Markt sucht Fachleute.\nA: Haben Sie eine Nachfrage?\nB: Ja, wie hoch ist das Gehalt?",exampleSrc:"A: The demand for IT experts is high.\nB: Yes, the market is looking for specialists.\nA: Do you have a question?\nB: Yes, how high is the salary?",funFact:"'Die Nachfrage nach Fachkräften ist hoch' (The demand for skilled workers is high). Also: 'Bei Nachfrage kontaktieren Sie uns' (For inquiries, contact us)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Auswahl",src:"the selection, the choice",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Aus (out) + Wahl (choice).\n'Eine große Auswahl' = a large selection.",example:"A: Die Auswahl der Kandidaten war schwer.\nB: Wie viele waren es?\nA: Dreißig für fünf Stellen.\nB: Eine große Auswahl also.",exampleSrc:"A: The selection of candidates was difficult.\nB: How many were there?\nA: Thirty for five positions.\nB: A large selection then.",funFact:"The hiring process involves an 'Auswahlverfahren' (selection procedure). Choosing FROM a group. Aus (out) + Wahl (choice)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Auswahl'?",opts:["the advertisement or classified ad","the competition","the selection/choice","the demand"],ans:"the selection/choice",hint:"A compound noun: Aus (out) + a word meaning option. When a company reviews applicants, they make this."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Konkurrenz",src:"the competition",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'concurrere' (to run together).\n'Die Konkurrenz ist stark.'",example:"A: Gibt es viel Konkurrenz?\nB: Ja, die Konkurrenz ist stark.\nA: Wie kann ich mich abheben?\nB: Mit einem perfekten Lebenslauf.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a lot of competition?\nB: Yes, the competition is strong.\nA: How can I stand out?\nB: With a perfect CV.",funFact:"Used for business competition and personal rivalry. The German job market can be very 'konkurrenzfähig' (competitive). From Latin 'concurrere' (to run together)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Empfang",src:"the reception",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'empfangen' (to receive).\nAlso means receiving a signal.",example:"A: Bitte melden Sie sich am Empfang.\nB: Wo ist der Empfang?\nA: Im Erdgeschoss, gleich links.\nB: Danke. Bis gleich.",exampleSrc:"A: Please report to reception.\nB: Where is the reception?\nA: On the ground floor, just to the left.\nB: Thank you. See you shortly.",funFact:"'Bitte melden Sie sich am Empfang' (Please report to reception). Also means receiving a signal: 'Kein Empfang' (no reception/signal)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kündigung",src:"the termination, the resignation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'kündigen' (to terminate).\nNotice periods: often 1-3 months.",example:"A: Ich habe meine Kündigung eingereicht.\nB: Warum?\nA: Ich habe eine bessere Stelle gefunden.\nB: Die Kündigungsfrist beträgt drei Monate.",exampleSrc:"A: I submitted my resignation.\nB: Why?\nA: I found a better position.\nB: The notice period is three months.",funFact:"In Germany, notice periods are strictly regulated: often 1 to 3 months. 'Ich habe meine Kündigung eingereicht' (I submitted my resignation). From 'kündigen.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Entlassung",src:"the dismissal, being let go",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ent- (away) + Lassung (letting).\nWhen the employer ends the contract.",example:"A: Er hat eine Entlassung bekommen.\nB: Warum wurde er entlassen?\nA: Die Firma baut Stellen ab.\nB: Das ist traurig.",exampleSrc:"A: He received a dismissal.\nB: Why was he let go?\nA: The company is cutting positions.\nB: That is sad.",funFact:"Kündigung can go either way (employee or employer). Entlassung is when the employer ends it. 'Massenentlassungen' (mass layoffs) make headlines."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich habe meine {1} eingereicht, weil ich eine bessere Stelle gefunden habe.",a:["Kündigung"],opts:["Kündigung","Entlassung","Bewerbung","Annonce"],hint:"When you resign from a job. The notice you submit to leave your employer.",sSrc:"I submitted my resignation because I found a better position."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Aktion",src:"the action, the campaign",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'actio.'\nAlso used for promotional campaigns.",example:"A: Wir starten eine neue Aktion.\nB: Was für eine Aktion?\nA: Eine Werbeaktion für unsere Produkte.\nB: Gute Idee. Wann geht es los?",exampleSrc:"A: We are starting a new campaign.\nB: What kind of campaign?\nA: A promotional campaign for our products.\nB: Good idea. When does it start?",funFact:"Same root as English 'action.' 'Eine Werbeaktion' (a promotional campaign). Also used for activist campaigns: 'Aktion gegen Armut' (Action against poverty)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Aktivität",src:"the activity",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'activitas.'\n'Freizeitaktivitäten' sometimes appear on German CVs.",example:"A: Welche Aktivitäten machen Sie in der Freizeit?\nB: Sport und Lesen.\nA: Schreiben Sie das in den Lebenslauf?\nB: Ja, in Deutschland ist das üblich.",exampleSrc:"A: What activities do you do in your free time?\nB: Sports and reading.\nA: Do you write that on the CV?\nB: Yes, in Germany that is customary.",funFact:"Yes, Germans sometimes list hobbies and 'Freizeitaktivitäten' on their CV. It is considered normal and can make a good impression."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Aufforderung",src:"the request, the call to action",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Auf (up) + Forderung (demand).\nStronger than a 'Bitte' (request).",example:"A: Das ist eine Aufforderung zur Bewerbung.\nB: Von welcher Firma?\nA: Von TechBerlin GmbH.\nB: Ich bewerbe mich sofort.",exampleSrc:"A: That is a call for applications.\nB: From which company?\nA: From TechBerlin GmbH.\nB: I will apply immediately.",funFact:"'Eine Aufforderung zur Bewerbung' (a call for applications). The Auf- prefix adds urgency. Stronger than 'bitten' (to ask politely)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Vortrag",src:"the presentation, the lecture",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Vor (before) + Trag (carrying).\nYou 'carry' ideas before an audience.",example:"A: Können Sie einen Vortrag halten?\nB: Ja, ich halte gern Vorträge.\nA: Über welches Thema?\nB: Über interkulturelle Kommunikation.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you give a presentation?\nB: Yes, I like giving presentations.\nA: On which topic?\nB: On intercultural communication.",funFact:"'Einen Vortrag halten' (to give a presentation) is a standard professional skill. You 'carry' your ideas before an audience."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Wir starten eine neue Aufforderung zur Bewerbung.' Was ist eine Aufforderung?",opts:["a formal cancellation notice","a request/call to action","an advertisement or listing","a selection process"],ans:"a request/call to action",hint:"Stronger than a 'Bitte.' Auf (up) + Forderung (demand). An urgent prompt for something."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l8b",title:"Der perfekte Lebenslauf (Teil 2)",icon:"✍️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der perfekte Lebenslauf (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Beweis",src:"the proof, the evidence",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'beweisen' (to prove).\n'Zeugnisse sind der Beweis.'",example:"A: Haben Sie einen Beweis für Ihre Erfahrung?\nB: Ja, hier sind meine Arbeitszeugnisse.\nA: Das ist der beste Beweis.\nB: Ich habe auch Referenzen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have proof of your experience?\nB: Yes, here are my work references.\nA: That is the best proof.\nB: I also have references.",funFact:"'Zeugnisse sind der Beweis für Ihre Qualifikation' (Certificates are proof of your qualification). In court: 'Beweismittel' (evidence/means of proof)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ablehnen",src:"to reject, to decline",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ab (off) + lehnen (to lean).\nLeaning away from something.",example:"A: Die Firma hat meine Bewerbung abgelehnt.\nB: Das tut mir leid. Warum?\nA: Sie sagten, mir fehlt Erfahrung.\nB: Versuch es bei einer anderen Firma.",exampleSrc:"A: The company rejected my application.\nB: I am sorry. Why?\nA: They said I lack experience.\nB: Try another company.",funFact:"'Die Bewerbung wurde abgelehnt' (The application was rejected). Leaning away from something. Separable: 'Ich lehne das Angebot ab.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"absagen",src:"to cancel, to turn down",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ab + sagen (to say).\nMore personal than ablehnen.",example:"A: Ich muss leider absagen.\nB: Schade. Warum?\nA: Ich habe schon eine andere Stelle angenommen.\nB: Verstehe. Viel Erfolg dort!",exampleSrc:"A: I unfortunately have to cancel.\nB: Too bad. Why?\nA: I already accepted another position.\nB: I understand. Good luck there!",funFact:"More personal than ablehnen. You 'absagen' to people, you 'ablehnen' offers or proposals. 'Ich muss leider absagen' is a polite refusal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"akzeptieren",src:"to accept",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. From Latin 'acceptare.'\nMore formal than 'annehmen.'",example:"A: Akzeptieren Sie das Angebot?\nB: Ja, ich akzeptiere es.\nA: Wunderbar! Willkommen im Team.\nB: Vielen Dank. Ich freue mich.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you accept the offer?\nB: Yes, I accept it.\nA: Wonderful! Welcome to the team.\nB: Thank you very much. I am pleased.",funFact:"Same word internationally. 'Das Angebot akzeptieren' (to accept the offer). Not separable. More formal than 'annehmen.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"annehmen",src:"to accept, to assume",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + nehmen (to take).\nAlso means 'to assume': 'Ich nehme an, dass...'",example:"A: Nehmen Sie das Angebot an?\nB: Ja, ich nehme es gern an.\nA: Sehr gut.\nB: Wann kann ich anfangen?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you accept the offer?\nB: Yes, I gladly accept it.\nA: Very good.\nB: When can I start?",funFact:"Separable: 'Ich nehme das Angebot an.' Also means 'to assume': 'Ich nehme an, dass...' (I assume that...). Double meaning depending on context."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausbilden",src:"to train, to educate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Aus + bilden (to form).\n'Wir bilden Lehrlinge aus.'",example:"A: Bilden Sie Lehrlinge aus?\nB: Ja, jedes Jahr fünf neue.\nA: In welchem Beruf?\nB: Als Mechatroniker.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you train apprentices?\nB: Yes, five new ones every year.\nA: In which profession?\nB: As mechatronics engineers.",funFact:"The Ausbildung (training) is the cornerstone of the German economy. Separable: 'Wir bilden Lehrlinge aus' (We train apprentices)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er hat das Angebot {1} und fängt nächste Woche an.",a:["angenommen"],opts:["angenommen","abgelehnt","akzeptiert","abgesagt"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to accept. The past participle form: an + ge + nommen.",sSrc:"He accepted the offer and starts next week."},
{type:"teach",trg:"auswählen",src:"to select, to pick",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Aus + wählen (to choose).\nChoosing one OUT of many.",example:"A: Wen haben Sie ausgewählt?\nB: Den Kandidaten aus Berlin.\nA: Warum ihn?\nB: Er hatte die besten Qualifikationen.",exampleSrc:"A: Whom did you select?\nB: The candidate from Berlin.\nA: Why him?\nB: He had the best qualifications.",funFact:"'Wir haben den besten Kandidaten ausgewählt' (We selected the best candidate). Separable. Choosing one OUT of many."},
{type:"teach",trg:"auffordern",src:"to request, to call upon",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Auf + fordern (to demand).\nStronger than 'bitten.'",example:"A: Wir fordern Sie auf, sich zu bewerben.\nB: Vielen Dank für die Einladung.\nA: Bitte senden Sie Ihre Unterlagen.\nB: Gern. Bis wann?",exampleSrc:"A: We invite you to apply.\nB: Thank you very much for the invitation.\nA: Please send your documents.\nB: Gladly. By when?",funFact:"'Wir fordern Sie auf, sich zu bewerben' (We invite you to apply). Separable and formal. Note: kündigen alone means 'to resign/fire.' The auf- prefix changes it completely."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Personalchef schrieb die Annonce und wählte drei Kandidaten aus. Welche Verben stehen im Präteritum?",opts:["Beide Verben sind Präsens, kein Präteritum","Nur wählte aus (kein schrieb)","schrieb und wählte","Nur schrieb die Annonce"],ans:"schrieb und wählte",hint:"Both verbs describe completed past actions in a narrative. One is strong (vowel change), one is weak (-te)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} mich sehr freuen, wenn Sie mich zum Gespräch einladen.",a:["würde"],opts:["würde","will","habe","bin"],hint:"A polite expression of a wish in a cover letter. 'I would be very pleased if...'",sSrc:"I would be very pleased if you invite me to the interview."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} mich auf die Stelle und {2} gern mehr erfahren.",blanks:{"1":"bewerbe","2":"würde"},pool:["bewerbe","würde","bewarb","will","könnte","muss"],hint:"Present tense for what you are doing now, Konjunktiv II for the polite wish.",sSrc:"I am applying for the position and would like to learn more."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"ablehnen",src:"to reject"},{trg:"annehmen",src:"to accept"},{trg:"absagen",src:"to cancel"},{trg:"auswählen",src:"to select"},{trg:"auffordern",src:"to request"},{trg:"ausbilden",src:"to train"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous-excited",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Verumius klickt auf 'Senden.' Stille. Dann dreht er sich zu Yilmaz. 'Das war's? Einfach so?' Yilmaz lächelt. 'Jetzt beginnt das Warten.'",src:"Verumius clicks 'Send.' Silence. Then he turns to Yilmaz. 'That's it? Just like that?' Yilmaz smiles. 'Now the waiting begins.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'der Beweis'?",opts:["the proof, the evidence","the advertisement","the classified ad","the presentation, the lecture"],ans:"the proof, the evidence",hint:"Be- prefix + weisen (to show/point). Something that shows the truth of a claim."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} Sie das Angebot?",a:["akzeptieren"],opts:["die Auswahl","das Inserat","die Entlassung","akzeptieren"],hint:"A Latin verb cognate meaning to agree to or receive. Same root as English 'accept'.",sSrc:"Do you accept the offer?"}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 9: Alles auf dem Prüfstand ====================
{id:"deu_r13l9",title:"Alles auf dem Prüfstand",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles auf dem Prüfstand",desc:"Test everything from Unit 13. Prove you can write a CV, hold a conversation, and use Präteritum and Konjunktiv II correctly.",goals:["Test everything from Unit 13","Master CV writing and conversation","Apply Präteritum and Konjunktiv II correctly"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"focused",art:"de-vhs-office-desk",trg:"Am Tag vor dem echten Vorstellungsgespräch. Yilmaz hat Verumius' gesamte Bewerbungsmappe auf dem Tisch ausgebreitet. Lebenslauf, Anschreiben, Zeugnisse. Alles muss sitzen.",src:"The day before the real job interview. Yilmaz has spread Verumius's entire application folder on the table. CV, cover letter, certificates. Everything must be perfect."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Anbieter",src:"the provider, the supplier",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. An + Bieter (bidder/offerer).\n'Internetanbieter' = internet provider.",example:"A: Wer ist Ihr Internetanbieter?\nB: Telekom. Und Ihrer?\nA: Vodafone. Die sind günstig.\nB: Ja, es gibt viele Anbieter in Deutschland.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is your internet provider?\nB: Telekom. And yours?\nA: Vodafone. They are affordable.\nB: Yes, there are many providers in Germany.",funFact:"'Internetanbieter' (internet provider), 'Dienstleistungsanbieter' (service provider). The -er ending makes it the person or company doing the offering."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Beratung",src:"the consulting, the advice",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'beraten' (to advise).\n'Berufsberatung' = career counseling.",example:"A: Brauchen Sie eine Beratung?\nB: Ja, eine Berufsberatung.\nA: Die Agentur für Arbeit bietet kostenlose Beratung.\nB: Gut zu wissen. Danke.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you need counseling?\nB: Yes, career counseling.\nA: The employment agency offers free counseling.\nB: Good to know. Thanks.",funFact:"'Berufsberatung' (career counseling) is free at the Agentur für Arbeit (employment agency). Germany offers professional Beratung for almost everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fremdsprache",src:"the foreign language",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Fremd (foreign) + Sprache (language).\nStandard on German CVs.",example:"A: Welche Fremdsprachen sprechen Sie?\nB: Englisch und Französisch.\nA: Auf welchem Niveau?\nB: Englisch fließend, Französisch B1.",exampleSrc:"A: Which foreign languages do you speak?\nB: English and French.\nA: At what level?\nB: English fluently, French B1.",funFact:"'Fremdsprachenkenntnisse' (foreign language skills) are standard on German CVs. English is the most common first Fremdsprache in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Muttersprache",src:"the mother tongue",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Mutter + Sprache.\nSame concept as English 'mother tongue.'",example:"A: Was ist Ihre Muttersprache?\nB: Türkisch.\nA: Und Ihre Fremdsprachen?\nB: Deutsch, Englisch und Arabisch.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your mother tongue?\nB: Turkish.\nA: And your foreign languages?\nB: German, English, and Arabic.",funFact:"Germans put this on their CV to distinguish from learned languages. 'Muttersprache: Deutsch' is how native speakers label it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zweitsprache",src:"the second language",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Zweit (second) + Sprache.\nLearned early, feels almost native.",example:"A: Deutsch ist meine Zweitsprache.\nB: Wirklich? Sie sprechen perfekt!\nA: Danke. Ich lebe seit 15 Jahren hier.\nB: Das hört man.",exampleSrc:"A: German is my second language.\nB: Really? You speak perfectly!\nA: Thanks. I have been living here for 15 years.\nB: One can tell.",funFact:"Different from Fremdsprache: a Zweitsprache is learned so early it feels almost native. Fremdsprache is learned later and feels foreign."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Fremdsprache und Zweitsprache?",opts:["Es gibt keinen wirklich wesentlichen Unterschied","Fremdsprache ist in Schulen formeller und schriftlicher","Zweitsprache wird früh gelernt und fühlt sich fast nativ an","Fremdsprache wird immer erst später im Leben erlernt"],ans:"Zweitsprache wird früh gelernt und fühlt sich fast nativ an",hint:"One is acquired early in life, deeply embedded. The other is studied later and often remains more conscious and deliberate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Kennzeichen",src:"the characteristic, the license plate",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Kenn (know) + Zeichen (sign).\nAlso means 'license plate.'",example:"A: Was sind die Kennzeichen eines guten Lebenslaufs?\nB: Struktur, Klarheit und Vollständigkeit.\nA: Und besondere Kennzeichen?\nB: Ihre individuellen Stärken.",exampleSrc:"A: What are the characteristics of a good CV?\nB: Structure, clarity, and completeness.\nA: And special characteristics?\nB: Your individual strengths.",funFact:"Also means 'license plate': your car's Kennzeichen identifies it. On forms: 'Besondere Kennzeichen' (special characteristics)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Matura",src:"the Matura (Austrian/Swiss school exam)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'maturus' (ripe/mature).\nAustrian and Swiss equivalent of Abitur.",example:"A: Haben Sie Matura oder Abitur?\nB: Matura. Ich komme aus Österreich.\nA: Das ist gleichwertig.\nB: Ja, Matura und Abitur sind dasselbe.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have the Matura or Abitur?\nB: Matura. I come from Austria.\nA: That is equivalent.\nB: Yes, Matura and Abitur are the same.",funFact:"Die Matura is the Austrian and Swiss equivalent of the German Abitur. Same exam, different name. You will encounter both terms when applying across German-speaking countries."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Führerausweis",src:"the driver's license (Swiss)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Führer (driver) + Ausweis (ID).\nSwiss German term. Germans say 'Führerschein.'",example:"A: Haben Sie einen Führerschein?\nB: In der Schweiz heißt das Führerausweis.\nA: Stimmt. Haben Sie einen?\nB: Ja, seit zehn Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a driver's license?\nB: In Switzerland it is called Führerausweis.\nA: Right. Do you have one?\nB: Yes, for ten years.",funFact:"Germans say 'Führerschein,' Swiss say 'Führerausweis.' Same document, regional vocabulary. This shows how German varies across countries."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mehrwertsteuer",src:"the value-added tax (VAT)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Mehr (more) + Wert (value) + Steuer (tax).\nCurrently 19% in Germany. Abbreviation: MwSt.",example:"A: Ist die Mehrwertsteuer inklusive?\nB: Ja, 19 Prozent MwSt.\nA: In der Schweiz ist sie niedriger.\nB: Stimmt. Dort sind es nur 8,1 Prozent.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the VAT included?\nB: Yes, 19 percent VAT.\nA: In Switzerland it is lower.\nB: Right. There it is only 8.1 percent.",funFact:"Die Mehrwertsteuer is currently 19% in Germany. Everyone knows the abbreviation: MwSt. The longest everyday compound in German tax vocabulary."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Profisportler",src:"the professional athlete (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Profi + Sportler (athlete).\nGermany produces many world-class athletes.",example:"A: Er ist Profisportler.\nB: In welcher Sportart?\nA: Fußball. Er spielt in der Bundesliga.\nB: Beeindruckend.",exampleSrc:"A: He is a professional athlete.\nB: In which sport?\nA: Football. He plays in the Bundesliga.\nB: Impressive.",funFact:"Germany's Bundesliga (football), Handball-Bundesliga, and Formula 1 produce many Profisportler. Sports vocabulary meets professional vocabulary."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Profisportlerin",src:"the professional athlete (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Profisportler + '-in.'\nGerman women's sports are growing enormously.",example:"A: Sie ist Profisportlerin.\nB: Wirklich? In welcher Sportart?\nA: Handball. Nationalmannschaft.\nB: Toll!",exampleSrc:"A: She is a professional athlete.\nB: Really? In which sport?\nA: Handball. National team.\nB: Great!",funFact:"German women's football has grown enormously. The national team has won multiple European Championships. Die Profisportlerin follows the standard -in pattern."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} in Deutschland beträgt 19 Prozent.",a:["Mehrwertsteuer"],opts:["Mehrwertsteuer","Nachfrage","Beratung","Konkurrenz"],hint:"The value-added tax. Abbreviated MwSt. A three-part compound: more + value + tax.",sSrc:"The VAT in Germany is 19 percent."}
]},
{id:"deu_r13l9b",title:"Alles auf dem Prüfstand (Teil 2)",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles auf dem Prüfstand (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"abhängig",src:"dependent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ab (off) + hängig (hanging).\nLiterally 'hanging from.' Also used for addiction.",example:"A: Ist das Ergebnis von mir abhängig?\nB: Ja, es hängt von Ihnen ab.\nA: Dann strenge ich mich an.\nB: Das ist die richtige Einstellung.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the result depend on me?\nB: Yes, it depends on you.\nA: Then I will make an effort.\nB: That is the right attitude.",funFact:"'Finanziell abhängig' (financially dependent). Also used for addiction: 'abhängig von Kaffee' (dependent on coffee). The opposite: 'unabhängig' (independent)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abwesend",src:"absent",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Ab (away) + wesend (being).\nThe opposite of anwesend.",example:"A: Herr Müller ist heute abwesend.\nB: Ist er krank?\nA: Ja, er hat sich krankgemeldet.\nB: Gute Besserung.",exampleSrc:"A: Mr. Müller is absent today.\nB: Is he sick?\nA: Yes, he called in sick.\nB: Get well soon.",funFact:"Ab- (away from) vs. an- (at/present). Perfect contrast pair: abwesend (absent) and anwesend (present)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anwesend",src:"present, in attendance",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"An (at) + wesend (being).\nRoll call vocabulary.",example:"A: Sind alle Mitarbeiter anwesend?\nB: Fast alle. Drei sind abwesend.\nA: Wer ist nicht anwesend?\nB: Frau Schulz, Herr Weber und Frau Klein.",exampleSrc:"A: Are all employees present?\nB: Almost all. Three are absent.\nA: Who is not present?\nB: Mrs. Schulz, Mr. Weber, and Mrs. Klein.",funFact:"'Alle Mitarbeiter sind anwesend' (All employees are present). Roll call vocabulary. Perfect contrast pair with abwesend."},
{type:"teach",trg:"angenehm",src:"pleasant, agreeable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'annehmen.' Pleasant.\n'Angenehm!' = Pleased to meet you!",example:"A: Angenehm! Mein Name ist Verumius.\nB: Freut mich! Ich bin Frau Schmidt.\nA: Die Arbeitsatmosphäre ist sehr angenehm.\nB: Ja, wir legen Wert darauf.",exampleSrc:"A: Pleased to meet you! My name is Verumius.\nB: Nice to meet you! I am Mrs. Schmidt.\nA: The work atmosphere is very pleasant.\nB: Yes, we value that.",funFact:"'Angenehm!' is what Germans say when introduced. Short for 'Es ist mir angenehm, Sie kennenzulernen' (It is pleasant to meet you)."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Angenehm! Mein Name ist Verumius.' Wann sagt man 'Angenehm!'?",opts:["Beim formellen Verabschieden","Bei einer Vorstellung","Beim Einreichen einer Beschwerde","Bei einer Bewerbung"],ans:"Bei einer Vorstellung",hint:"What Germans say when meeting someone for the first time. Short for 'It is pleasant to meet you.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"achten",src:"to pay attention to, to respect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Related to 'Achtung' (attention).\nNot to be confused with acht (eight).",example:"A: Achten Sie auf die Details.\nB: Ja, ich achte immer auf Details.\nA: Sehr gut. Das ist wichtig.\nB: Besonders bei Bewerbungen.",exampleSrc:"A: Pay attention to the details.\nB: Yes, I always pay attention to details.\nA: Very good. That is important.\nB: Especially with applications.",funFact:"Related to 'Achtung' (attention). 'Ich achte darauf' (I pay attention to that). Not to be confused with the number acht (eight)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ankündigen",src:"to announce",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + kündigen (to announce).\nNote: kündigen alone means 'to resign/fire.'",example:"A: Die Firma kündigt Veränderungen an.\nB: Welche Veränderungen?\nA: Neue Arbeitszeiten.\nB: Das wurde letzte Woche angekündigt.",exampleSrc:"A: The company announces changes.\nB: What changes?\nA: New working hours.\nB: That was announced last week.",funFact:"Separable: 'Die Firma kündigt Veränderungen an.' Note: kündigen alone means 'to resign/fire.' The an- prefix changes the meaning entirely."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anschaffen",src:"to purchase, to acquire",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + schaffen (to create).\nMore formal than 'kaufen.'",example:"A: Wir müssen neue Computer anschaffen.\nB: Wie viele?\nA: Zehn Stück. Für die neue Abteilung.\nB: Das kostet viel Geld.",exampleSrc:"A: We need to purchase new computers.\nB: How many?\nA: Ten units. For the new department.\nB: That costs a lot of money.",funFact:"Used for business purchases. More formal than 'kaufen' (to buy). Separable: 'Wir schaffen neue Geräte an.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"anstellen",src:"to hire, to employ",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + stellen (to place).\nSame meaning as 'einstellen.'",example:"A: Wir stellen neue Mitarbeiter an.\nB: Wie viele?\nA: Fünf für die IT-Abteilung.\nB: Wann fangen sie an?",exampleSrc:"A: We are hiring new employees.\nB: How many?\nA: Five for the IT department.\nB: When do they start?",funFact:"Same meaning as 'einstellen.' Separable. Also colloquial: 'Was stellst du an?' (What are you up to/doing?)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anstrengen",src:"to exhaust, to make an effort",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + strengen (to tighten).\nReflexive: 'Ich strenge mich an.'",example:"A: Die Arbeit strengt mich an.\nB: Ist es zu viel?\nA: Nein, ich strenge mich gern an.\nB: Das sieht man. Gute Arbeit!",exampleSrc:"A: The work exhausts me.\nB: Is it too much?\nA: No, I like making an effort.\nB: One can tell. Good work!",funFact:"Reflexive: 'Ich strenge mich an' (I make an effort). The more you tighten yourself, the harder you work. The noun: Anstrengung (effort)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Im Lebenslauf steht: 'Ich ging zur Universität und studierte Architektur.' Wie sagst du das im Perfekt?",opts:["Ich bin zur Universität gegangen und habe Architektur studiert","Ich gehe jeden Tag zur Universität und studiere Architektur","Ich werde nächstes Jahr zur Universität gehen und Architektur studieren","Ich würde sehr gern zur Universität gehen und Architektur studieren"],ans:"Ich bin zur Universität gegangen und habe Architektur studiert",hint:"Both actions need Perfekt. One expresses movement to a location and uses one auxiliary. The other is a learning activity ending in -ieren, needing the other auxiliary and no ge- prefix."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} mich über eine Einladung zum Gespräch freuen.",a:["würde"],opts:["würde","will","habe","wurde"],hint:"A polite wish for something you hope will happen. Watch the spelling closely: the correct form means 'would,' not 'became.'",sSrc:"I would be pleased about an invitation to the interview."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Dürfte ich Sie etwas fragen?' Welches Modalverb steht im Konjunktiv II?",opts:["dürfen","sollen","müssen","können"],ans:"dürfen",hint:"The question 'Dürfte ich Sie etwas fragen?' is a very soft request for permission. Which base modal verb does 'dürfte' derive from?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} bei Siemens und {2} gern wieder dort {3}.",blanks:{"1":"arbeitete","2":"würde","3":"arbeiten"},pool:["arbeitete","würde","arbeiten","arbeite","wurde","gearbeitet"],hint:"First blank: narrative past tense for CV history (one completed action). Second blank: a polite wish construction using an auxiliary that triggers the infinitive at the end.",sSrc:"I worked at Siemens and would gladly work there again."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Muttersprache",src:"mother tongue"},{trg:"Fremdsprache",src:"foreign language"},{trg:"Zweitsprache",src:"second language"},{trg:"fließend",src:"fluent"},{trg:"Anbieter",src:"provider"},{trg:"Beratung",src:"consulting"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius will schreiben: 'Ich kann Ihr Team verstärken, weil ich drei Sprachen spreche.' Wie macht er den Satz höflicher?",opts:["Ich muss Ihr Team sofort verstärken, weil ich drei Sprachen spreche","Ich könnte Ihr Team verstärken, da ich drei Sprachen fließend spreche","Ich werde auf jeden Fall Ihr Team verstärken, ob ich Sprachen spreche","Ich kann Ihr Team leider nicht verstärken, denn ich spreche keine Sprachen"],ans:"Ich könnte Ihr Team verstärken, da ich drei Sprachen fließend spreche",hint:"Replace 'kann' with its Konjunktiv II form. Use 'da' instead of 'weil' for a more formal register."},
{type:"fb",s:"Könnten Sie mir bitte {1}, wann das Gespräch stattfindet?",a:["sagen"],opts:["sagen","gesagt","sage","sagte"],hint:"Könnten Sie + Infinitiv at the end. A polite request for information.",sSrc:"Could you please tell me when the interview takes place?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'abhängig'?",opts:["pleasant, agreeable","the second language","dependent","the driver's license (Swiss)"],ans:"dependent",hint:"Ab- (from/off) + hängen (to hang). Literally 'hanging from' something."},
{type:"fb",s:"Herr Müller ist heute {1}.",a:["abwesend"],opts:["die Zweitsprache","anstellen","der Profisportler","abwesend"],hint:"Ab- (away) + wesend (being). Not here, not physically at the workplace today.",sSrc:"Mr. Müller is absent today."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'anwesend'?",opts:["the professional athlete (female)","to exhaust, to make an effort","the provider, the supplier","present, in attendance"],ans:"present, in attendance",hint:"An- (at) + wesend (being). The opposite of 'abwesend'. Physically here."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} Sie auf die Details.",a:["achten"],opts:["achten","abwesend","der Anbieter","die Mehrwertsteuer"],hint:"A verb meaning to heed or respect. Related to Acht (attention) in 'Acht geben'.",sSrc:"Pay attention to the details."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'ankündigen'?",opts:["the consulting, the advice","the mother tongue","to announce","to hire, to employ"],ans:"to announce",hint:"An- (on/toward) + kündigen (to notify). To make something publicly known."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir müssen neue Computer {1}.",a:["anschaffen"],opts:["anwesend","anschaffen","die Beratung","anstrengen"],hint:"An- + schaffen (to create/produce). To procure or acquire something new.",sSrc:"We need to purchase new computers."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'anstellen'?",opts:["pleasant, agreeable","to announce","the driver's license (Swiss)","to hire, to employ"],ans:"to hire, to employ",hint:"An- + stellen (to place). To place someone into a position at a company."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to exhaust, to make an effort' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["anstrengen"],opts:["angenehm","anstrengen","ankündigen","achten"],hint:"An- + strengen (from streng, strict). To push oneself rigorously.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to exhaust, to make an effort' in German?"}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 10: Die gute Nachricht ====================
{id:"deu_r13l10",title:"Die gute Nachricht",icon:"🎉",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die gute Nachricht",desc:"Read a formal acceptance email. Learn essential workplace verbs. Celebrate with Verumius and his friends.",goals:["Read a formal acceptance email","Learn essential workplace verbs","Celebrate with Verumius and his friends"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"excited",art:"de-verumius-apartment-laptop",trg:"Verumius' Wohnung. Später Abend. Er sitzt an seinem Laptop, die Kaffeetasse leer. Eine E-Mail-Benachrichtigung erscheint. Der Absender: Personalabteilung, TechBerlin GmbH.",src:"Verumius's apartment. Late evening. He sits at his laptop, the coffee cup empty. An email notification appears. The sender: HR Department, TechBerlin GmbH."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"suspenseful",art:"de-verumius-apartment-laptop",trg:"Die E-Mail beginnt: 'Sehr geehrter Herr Verumius, wir freuen uns, Ihnen mitzuteilen, dass wir Sie für die Stelle ausgewählt haben...'",src:"The email begins: 'Dear Mr. Verumius, we are pleased to inform you that we have selected you for the position...'"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"ecstatic",trg:"JA! Ich habe die Stelle! Dr. Yilmaz hatte recht, die Vorbereitung hat sich gelohnt!",src:"YES! I got the job! Dr. Yilmaz was right, the preparation paid off!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"happy",trg:"Verumius tippt eine Nachricht an Lukas: 'Lukas! Ich habe den Job bekommen!'",src:"Verumius types a message to Lukas: 'Lukas! I got the job!'"},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"excited",trg:"Alter! Krass! Das müssen wir feiern. Freitag Kneipe?",src:"Dude! Awesome! We have to celebrate. Friday at the bar?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"happy",trg:"Ja!",src:"Yes!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"casual",trg:"Ich bring meine Gitarre mit.",src:"I'll bring my guitar."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mühe",src:"the effort, the trouble",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. 'Die Mühe lohnt sich' = The effort is worth it.\nRelated to English 'moil' (to toil).",example:"A: Vielen Dank für Ihre Mühe.\nB: Gern geschehen. Es war keine Mühe.\nA: Doch, Sie haben sich viel Mühe gegeben.\nB: Es hat sich gelohnt.",exampleSrc:"A: Thank you very much for your effort.\nB: You're welcome. It was no trouble.\nA: Yes it was, you put in a lot of effort.\nB: It was worth it.",funFact:"'Vielen Dank für Ihre Mühe' is a formal closing line that thanks someone for their effort. 'Die Mühe lohnt sich' (The effort is worth it)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anhaben",src:"to wear, to have on",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + haben.\n'Was hast du an?' = What are you wearing?",example:"A: Was hast du morgen an?\nB: Meinen besten Anzug.\nA: Gute Idee. Der erste Eindruck zählt.\nB: Ja, ich will professionell aussehen.",exampleSrc:"A: What will you wear tomorrow?\nB: My best suit.\nA: Good idea. The first impression counts.\nB: Yes, I want to look professional.",funFact:"'Was hast du an?' (What are you wearing?). Separable. More casual than 'tragen' (to wear/carry). Perfect for informal conversation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ansprechen",src:"to address, to bring up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + sprechen.\nTwo meanings: talking TO and talking ABOUT.",example:"A: Darf ich Sie ansprechen?\nB: Natürlich.\nA: Ich möchte das Thema Gehalt ansprechen.\nB: Gern. Was stellen Sie sich vor?",exampleSrc:"A: May I address you?\nB: Of course.\nA: I would like to bring up the topic of salary.\nB: Gladly. What do you have in mind?",funFact:"Two meanings: 'Darf ich Sie ansprechen?' (May I address you?) and 'Das Thema ansprechen' (to bring up the topic). Talking TO and talking ABOUT."},
{type:"fb",s:"Darf ich das Thema Gehalt {1}?",a:["ansprechen"],opts:["ansprechen","anhaben","anwenden","anzeigen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to address or bring up a topic. An + sprechen.",sSrc:"May I bring up the topic of salary?"},
{type:"teach",trg:"anwenden",src:"to apply, to use",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + wenden (to turn).\nApplying knowledge in practice.",example:"A: Können Sie Ihre Kenntnisse anwenden?\nB: Ja, ich wende mein Wissen täglich an.\nA: Die Anwendung ist wichtiger als die Theorie.\nB: Da stimme ich zu.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you apply your knowledge?\nB: Yes, I apply my knowledge daily.\nA: Application is more important than theory.\nB: I agree.",funFact:"What you learned in theory, you 'anwenden' in practice. 'Anwendung' (application) is the noun form. Separable verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anzeigen",src:"to display, to report, to advertise",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An + zeigen (to show).\nAlso: 'jemanden anzeigen' = to report to police.",example:"A: Die Firma zeigt die Stelle online an.\nB: Auf welcher Webseite?\nA: Auf Indeed und LinkedIn.\nB: Gut. Ich schaue sofort nach.",exampleSrc:"A: The company advertises the position online.\nB: On which website?\nA: On Indeed and LinkedIn.\nB: Good. I will check right away.",funFact:"'Eine Stelle anzeigen' (to advertise a position). Also: 'Jemanden anzeigen' (to report someone to police). 'Anzeige' is both an ad and a police report."},
{type:"teach",trg:"begleiten",src:"to accompany",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Be- + gleiten (to glide).\nTo glide alongside someone.",example:"A: Darf ich Sie zum Büro begleiten?\nB: Ja, gern. Ich kenne den Weg noch nicht.\nA: Kommen Sie. Ich begleite Sie.\nB: Vielen Dank.",exampleSrc:"A: May I accompany you to the office?\nB: Yes, gladly. I don't know the way yet.\nA: Come along. I will accompany you.\nB: Thank you very much.",funFact:"The be- prefix makes it transitive. Gleiten alone means to glide. Together: to glide alongside someone. 'Darf ich Sie begleiten?' is polite and formal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bekanntgeben",src:"to announce, to make known",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Bekannt (known) + geben (to give).\nMaking something known to everyone.",example:"A: Wann geben Sie die Ergebnisse bekannt?\nB: Morgen Nachmittag.\nA: Per E-Mail?\nB: Ja, wir geben alles per E-Mail bekannt.",exampleSrc:"A: When will you announce the results?\nB: Tomorrow afternoon.\nA: By email?\nB: Yes, we announce everything by email.",funFact:"'Die Firma gibt die Ergebnisse bekannt' (The company announces the results). Separable. Making something known to everyone."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'bekanntgeben'?",opts:["to accompany someone","to obtain or acquire","to announce/make known","to report to the police"],ans:"to announce/make known",hint:"A separable verb built from two parts. The result is making information public or official."},
{type:"teach",trg:"benötigen",src:"to require, to need",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. More formal than 'brauchen.'\nStandard in business correspondence.",example:"A: Welche Unterlagen benötigen Sie?\nB: Lebenslauf und Zeugnisse.\nA: Benötigen Sie auch ein Foto?\nB: Ja, bitte.",exampleSrc:"A: Which documents do you need?\nB: CV and certificates.\nA: Do you also need a photo?\nB: Yes, please.",funFact:"'Wir benötigen Ihre Unterlagen' (We require your documents). Standard in business correspondence. More formal than 'brauchen.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"besorgen",src:"to obtain, to get",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Be- + sorgen (to care).\nAlso: 'besorgt sein' = to be worried.",example:"A: Können Sie mir die Unterlagen besorgen?\nB: Ja, ich besorge sie bis morgen.\nA: Danke. Das ist sehr hilfreich.\nB: Kein Problem.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you get me the documents?\nB: Yes, I will get them by tomorrow.\nA: Thanks. That is very helpful.\nB: No problem.",funFact:"Two meanings depending on context: 'besorgen' (to obtain/get) and 'besorgt sein' (to be worried). The meaning changes with reflexive use."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beweisen",src:"to prove",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Strong verb: beweisen/bewies/bewiesen.\nIn job contexts: proving your worth.",example:"A: Können Sie Ihre Qualifikation beweisen?\nB: Ja, hier sind meine Zeugnisse.\nA: Das beweist Ihre Erfahrung.\nB: Ich habe auch Referenzen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you prove your qualification?\nB: Yes, here are my certificates.\nA: That proves your experience.\nB: I also have references.",funFact:"Strong verb: beweisen/bewies/bewiesen. 'Das beweist seine Qualifikation' (That proves his qualification). Be- + weisen (to show/point)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erfordern",src:"to require, to demand",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. Er- + fordern (to demand).\nMore formal than 'brauchen.'",example:"A: Die Stelle erfordert Erfahrung.\nB: Wie viel Erfahrung?\nA: Mindestens drei Jahre.\nB: Das erfülle ich.",exampleSrc:"A: The position requires experience.\nB: How much experience?\nA: At least three years.\nB: I meet that requirement.",funFact:"'Die Stelle erfordert Erfahrung' (The position requires experience). Not separable. The official word in job listings. More formal than 'brauchen.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Verb bedeutet 'to announce' oder 'to make known'?",opts:["begleiten","bekanntgeben","besorgen und kaufen","dringend benötigen"],ans:"bekanntgeben",hint:"A separable verb combining 'bekannt' (known) with 'geben' (to give)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Stelle {1} mindestens drei Jahre Erfahrung.",a:["erfordert"],opts:["erfordert","begleitet","besorgt","anwendet"],hint:"A formal verb meaning to require or demand. Not separable, with the er- prefix.",sSrc:"The position requires at least three years of experience."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Mühe",src:"effort"},{trg:"ansprechen",src:"to address/bring up"},{trg:"anwenden",src:"to apply/use"},{trg:"begleiten",src:"to accompany"},{trg:"benötigen",src:"to require"},{trg:"beweisen",src:"to prove"}]}
]},

// ==================== LESSON 11: Formell und informell ====================
{id:"deu_r13l11",title:"Formell und informell",icon:"📧",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Formell und informell",desc:"Learn remaining workplace vocabulary. Compare formal and informal German registers. Review all constructs from Unit 13.",goals:["Learn remaining workplace vocabulary","Compare formal and informal German registers","Review all constructs from Unit 13"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"erkundigen",src:"to inquire",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Always reflexive: 'sich erkundigen nach.'\nFormal and polite.",example:"A: Ich erkundige mich nach der Stelle.\nB: Gern. Was möchten Sie wissen?\nA: Wann beginnt die Stelle?\nB: Am ersten April.",exampleSrc:"A: I am inquiring about the position.\nB: Gladly. What would you like to know?\nA: When does the position start?\nB: On the first of April.",funFact:"Always reflexive: 'Ich erkundige mich nach der Stelle' (I inquire about the position). Formal and polite. What you do before applying."},
{type:"teach",trg:"funktionieren",src:"to function, to work",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Not separable. From French 'fonctionner.'\n'Das funktioniert!' = That works!",example:"A: Funktioniert der Drucker?\nB: Nein, er funktioniert nicht.\nA: Seit wann funktioniert er nicht?\nB: Seit gestern.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the printer work?\nB: No, it doesn't work.\nA: Since when doesn't it work?\nB: Since yesterday.",funFact:"One of the most-used words in everyday German. Pronounced 'funk-tsio-NEE-ren.' 'Das funktioniert!' (That works!) is said constantly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"handeln",src:"to act, to trade, to negotiate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Es handelt sich um...' = It concerns...\nDer Handel = trade. Die Handlung = plot/action.",example:"A: Worum handelt es sich?\nB: Es handelt sich um eine neue Stelle.\nA: Wie sollen wir handeln?\nB: Schnell. Die Frist endet bald.",exampleSrc:"A: What is it about?\nB: It is about a new position.\nA: How should we act?\nB: Quickly. The deadline ends soon.",funFact:"'Es handelt sich um...' (It concerns...) is formal German for introducing a topic. Covers action, commerce, and negotiation. Der Handel = trade."},
{type:"teach",trg:"melden",src:"to report, to register",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Sich melden' = to get in touch.\n'Bitte melden Sie sich am Empfang.'",example:"A: Bitte melden Sie sich am Empfang.\nB: Gut. Wo ist der Empfang?\nA: Im Erdgeschoss.\nB: Ich melde mich sofort.",exampleSrc:"A: Please report to reception.\nB: Good. Where is reception?\nA: On the ground floor.\nB: I will report right away.",funFact:"'Sich melden' (to get in touch, to report). 'Bitte melden Sie sich am Empfang.' Essential for German bureaucracy. Also used for raising your hand in class."},
{type:"fb",s:"Bitte {1} Sie sich am Empfang.",a:["melden"],opts:["melden","handeln","funktionieren","erkundigen"],hint:"A reflexive verb meaning to report or register. Essential for German bureaucracy.",sSrc:"Please report to reception."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Absenderin",src:"the sender (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ab (from) + Senderin.\nThe person who sends a letter or email.",example:"A: Wer ist die Absenderin?\nB: Die Personalabteilung.\nA: Die Absenderin schreibt sehr höflich.\nB: Ja, formelle E-Mails sind immer höflich.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is the sender?\nB: The HR department.\nA: The sender writes very politely.\nB: Yes, formal emails are always polite.",funFact:"'Absender/Absenderin' appears on every German letter and official email. The female sender. Ab (from) + Senderin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"meinetwegen",src:"for my sake, as far as I'm concerned",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Meinet (my) + wegen (because of).\nCan be generous or dismissive depending on tone.",example:"A: Soll ich Freitag kommen?\nB: Meinetwegen. Freitag passt.\nA: Bist du sicher?\nB: Ja, meinetwegen gern.",exampleSrc:"A: Should I come on Friday?\nB: Fine by me. Friday works.\nA: Are you sure?\nB: Yes, fine by me.",funFact:"'Meinetwegen kannst du gehen' (For all I care, you can go). Can be generous or dismissive depending on tone. Combines 'my' with 'because of.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"halbtags",src:"half-day, mornings/afternoons only",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Halb (half) + tags (during the day).\nDifferent from Teilzeit: specifically half a day.",example:"A: Arbeiten Sie halbtags?\nB: Ja, nur vormittags.\nA: Von wann bis wann?\nB: Von acht bis zwölf.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you work half-days?\nB: Yes, only mornings.\nA: From when to when?\nB: From eight to twelve.",funFact:"Different from Teilzeit: halbtags is specifically half a day, Teilzeit can be any reduced hours. 'Halbtags arbeiten' (to work half-days)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"perfekt",src:"perfect",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'perfectus' (completed).\nAlso the name of a German past tense.",example:"A: Dein Lebenslauf ist perfekt!\nB: Wirklich?\nA: Ja, perfekt strukturiert.\nB: Danke! Das freut mich.",exampleSrc:"A: Your CV is perfect!\nB: Really?\nA: Yes, perfectly structured.\nB: Thanks! That makes me happy.",funFact:"Same word in English and German. 'Dein Lebenslauf ist perfekt!' Also the name of the German past tense 'Perfekt' (Ich habe gemacht). Double meaning: the grammar tense and the adjective."},
{type:"tip",title:"Formal vs. Informal: Two Worlds",text:"The acceptance email:\n'Sehr geehrter Herr Verumius, wir freuen uns, Ihnen mitzuteilen...'\n\nLukas' message:\n'Alter! Krass!'\n\nSame language, two worlds.\n\nFormal German: Konjunktiv II, complete sentences, Sie, long words.\nInformal German: du, slang, abbreviations, voice messages.\n\nBoth are correct. The art is knowing when to use which.",deepDive:{title:"Switching Registers: A Key Skill",text:"In a job interview:\n'Ich würde mich freuen, von Ihnen zu hören.'\n\nIn the WhatsApp group:\n'Yo, hab den Job! Party?'\n\nGerman has more register levels than English.\nThe same person might use:\n1. Formal (applications, government offices)\n2. Standard (work, teachers)\n3. Informal (friends, family)\n4. Colloquial (slang, youth language)\n\nVerumius needs to understand all four.\n\nPhone etiquette: Always answer the phone with your name:\n'Müller, guten Tag.' Never just say 'Hallo?'\n\nLabor law basics:\nAfter probation: notice period = 4 weeks to the 15th or month end.\nWorks council must be consulted before termination.\nSick note: 6 weeks full salary."}},

{type:"tip",title:"The Application Process: Eight Steps",text:"The typical application process in Germany:\n\n1. Find a job listing (Stellenanzeige)\n2. Write the application: cover letter (Anschreiben), CV (Lebenslauf), and references (Zeugnisse)\n3. Send the application (by email or portal)\n4. Receive an interview invitation\n5. Job interview (Vorstellungsgespräch)\n6. Acceptance (Zusage) or rejection (Absage)\n7. Sign the contract\n8. Probation period begins (usually 6 months)",deepDive:{title:"Patience Required",text:"The process takes weeks to months.\nLarge companies: phone interview + in-person interview + assessment center.\nAcceptance: 1-2 weeks to decide.\nRejection: usually by email or letter.\n\nIt is completely normal to write 20-50 applications before getting an offer. Do not give up!"}},
{type:"tip",title:"The Cover Letter: Structure",text:"A German Anschreiben has 10 parts:\n\n1. Sender (your address, top right)\n2. Recipient (company, left)\n3. Place and date: Berlin, den 15. März 2026\n4. Subject line (bold, without 'Betreff:')\n5. Greeting: Sehr geehrte Damen und Herren,\n6. Introduction\n7. Main body\n8. Closing\n9. Sign-off: Mit freundlichen Grüßen\n10. Signature\n\nMaximum ONE page. After the greeting: comma, then new line.",deepDive:{title:"Formal Letters: The Sie Rule",text:"In formal letters and emails, Sie is ALWAYS capitalized:\nIhnen, Ihrer, Ihrem, Ihre\n\nThis also applies to emails.\n'Ich freue mich, von Ihnen zu hören.'\n'Könnten Sie mir Ihre Unterlagen zusenden?'\n\nDate format: Day. Month Year\nBerlin, den 15. März 2026 (not: März 15, 2026)"}},
{type:"tip",title:"The Sie Form in Job Interviews",text:"Job interviews in Germany ALWAYS use Sie.\nNever switch to du unless the interviewer explicitly offers it.\nEven then, some candidates stay with Sie.",deepDive:{title:"Offering the Du",text:"The transition from Sie to du is called 'das Duzen anbieten.'\nTraditionally, the higher-ranking person offers the Du.\n\nIn startups, du is often used from the start.\nWhen in doubt: always use Sie.\n\n'Sollen wir uns duzen?' = Shall we use du?\n'Gern! Ich bin Thomas.' = The switch happens."}},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz gehört in eine formelle Zusage-E-Mail?",opts:["Hey super, du hast den Job! Wir freuen uns! Komm einfach Montag.","Ja, mega cool! Bis nächsten Montag dann, tschüß!","Wir würden uns freuen, Sie in unserem Team zu begrüßen.","Krass, Alter! Willkommen im ganzen Team!"],ans:"Wir würden uns freuen, Sie in unserem Team zu begrüßen.",hint:"Formal emails use Konjunktiv II, polite address, and complete sentences."},
{type:"fb",s:"Er {1} drei Jahre in Istanbul und kam dann nach Berlin.",a:["studierte"],opts:["studierte","studiert","studieren","studiere"],hint:"Narrative past in a CV context. A regular verb in the Präteritum takes -te.",sSrc:"He studied three years in Istanbul and then came to Berlin."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius schreibt an die Firma: 'Könnten Sie mir bitte den Vertrag zusenden?' Warum könnten und nicht können?",opts:["Es gibt keinen Unterschied zwischen den beiden","Könnten ist höflicher und formeller","Können wäre hier grammatisch falsch","Könnten und können bedeuten etwas anderes"],ans:"Könnten ist höflicher und formeller",hint:"The Konjunktiv II of modals softens requests. Professional correspondence always prefers the polite form."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} mir, Ihnen {2}, dass ich die Stelle gern {3} möchte.",blanks:{"1":"erlaube","2":"mitzuteilen","3":"annehmen"},pool:["erlaube","mitzuteilen","annehmen","erlaubte","mitteilen","angenommen"],hint:"A formal response: 'I allow myself to inform you that I would like to accept the position.'",sSrc:"I allow myself to inform you that I would like to accept the position."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Bewerbung",src:"application"},{trg:"Lebenslauf",src:"CV/resume"},{trg:"Vorstellungsgespräch",src:"job interview"},{trg:"Kündigung",src:"termination"},{trg:"Mühe",src:"effort"},{trg:"Erfolg",src:"success"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas schreibt: 'Alter! Krass!' Die Firma schreibt: 'Sehr geehrter Herr Verumius.' Was zeigt dieser Kontrast?",opts:["Lukas beherrscht die deutsche Grammatik noch nicht ausreichend","Die Firma antwortet hier in einem sehr unangemessenen Ton","Verumius versteht den Inhalt der Nachricht von Lukas nicht","Formelles und informelles Register in derselben Sprache"],ans:"Formelles und informelles Register in derselben Sprache",hint:"Lukas writes like he would to a friend. The company writes formally. What does this contrast demonstrate about language?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"proud",art:"de-verumius-apartment-evening",trg:"Eine Sprachnachricht von Lukas: 'Ey, ich wollte nur sagen... ich bin stolz auf dich, Alter. Vom ersten Tag an, als du kein Wort Deutsch konntest. Und jetzt? Job in Berlin. Respekt.'",src:"A voice message from Lukas: 'Hey, I just wanted to say... I am proud of you, dude. From day one, when you couldn't speak a word of German. And now? Job in Berlin. Respect.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Wir {1} uns, Ihnen mitzuteilen, dass wir Sie ausgewählt haben.",a:["freuen"],opts:["freuen","würden","können","haben"],hint:"The standard opening of a positive reply from an employer. 'We are pleased to inform you...'",sSrc:"We are pleased to inform you that we have selected you."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} mich nach der offenen Stelle in Ihrer Firma.",a:["erkundige"],opts:["erkundige","melde","handle","funktioniere"],hint:"A reflexive verb meaning to inquire. Formal and polite, used when asking about a position.",sSrc:"I am inquiring about the open position in your company."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wer ist die ___ dieser E-Mail?",opts:["Absenderin","Bewerbung","Kündigung","Empfehlung"],ans:"Absenderin",hint:"The feminine form of the person who sent a letter or email."},
{type:"fb",s:"Soll ich Freitag kommen? {1}, das passt mir.",a:"Meinetwegen",opts:["Meinetwegen","Halbtags","Perfekt","Eindeutig"],hint:"An adverb meaning 'as far as I am concerned' or 'fine by me.'",sSrc:"Should I come on Friday? Fine by me, that works."},
{type:"mc",q:"Sie arbeitet nur vormittags, von acht bis zwölf. Sie arbeitet ___.",opts:["halbtags","perfekt","fließend","offiziell"],ans:"halbtags",hint:"An adverb meaning only half the working day, mornings or afternoons."},
{type:"fb",s:"Dein Lebenslauf ist {1} strukturiert!",a:"perfekt",opts:["perfekt","komplett","bestimmt","eindeutig"],hint:"This adjective means flawless, without any mistakes at all.",sSrc:"Your CV is perfectly structured!"}
]}

]};

